# -- LLM Backend Design ---------------------------------------------------------

# -- Completed Features (Production) --------------------------------------------

# -- Data egress model (2026-07-12) ---------------------------------------------
# The audit asked a question the graph could not answer: "which features send user
# data off-device?" — the single most important privacy question for a local-first,
# privacy-by-default app. It was unanswerable because egress was never modeled.
#
# THE LINE IS EXPORT vs DISTRIBUTION, not private vs public:
#
#   EXPORT is a RIGHT. Plain-text/TTL export of your own graph to your own disk is
#   NEVER blocked. Blocking it would be data lock-in, and it is futile anyway — the
#   graph sits in IndexedDB and can be read out regardless. Advisory header only.
#
#   DISTRIBUTION is a PRIVILEGE. When Reckons.AI is the INTERMEDIARY that hands
#   content to someone else — publish to the web, a share link, the exchange, a guest
#   view, a third-party sync — the app is participating in delivery, so it gates.
#
# What the user does with an exported file afterwards is their business (F66's
# principle, SAFETY.md). The gate binds where WE are in the loop, and nowhere else —
# claiming otherwise would be overclaiming a control we cannot exercise.

# -- Adult content policy (F66.1) — DECIDED 2026-07-12: OPTION C -----------------
# The goal: DO NOT block a romance author writing explicit fiction, while refusing to
# help distribute abuse material.
#
# WE GATE ONLY WHAT WE CARRY. Reckons.AI provides no mediated distribution channel for
# adult content. Write it, keep it, export it, self-host it — all unimpeded. We simply
# will not be the one handing it to strangers. That is a refusal to CARRY, not a
# refusal to LET YOU HAVE, and the difference is the whole policy.
#
# The decisive property of Option C: it deletes the gameable attestation entirely.
# There is NO purpose declaration, NO T&C tier-unlock, NO context field — because
# CONTEXT IS NEVER AN INPUT TO THE GATE. Nobody can talk their way past a gate that
# asks no question. The blackmailer who wraps their material in a plausible paragraph
# about their novel has nothing to wrap it in. It also means no accounts, no server, no
# PII, no retention duty, and no age-verification exposure — the app stays local-first.

kb:nemo-speech rdf:type     ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "NVIDIA NeMo Speech" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:description  "GPU-accelerated STT and TTS via NVIDIA NeMo (Apache 2.0). Python sidecar or Docker container. Models: Nemotron-3.5-ASR-Streaming-0.6B (40 languages, 80ms-1s latency), MagpieTTS v2602 (9 languages). Requires NVIDIA GPU + CUDA. Fallback to existing Whisper+Kokoro WASM for non-NVIDIA users." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:whisper-stt ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:kokoro-tts ;
               kpred:open-question "Sidecar architecture: Docker Compose, standalone FastAPI, or Ollama-style model runner? Need /transcribe and /synthesize HTTP endpoints matching existing provider pattern." ;
               kpred:open-question "Dev setup: separate repo or monorepo subfolder like mcp-server/? Python 3.12+ with uv for dependency management." .

kb:cosmos-nano rdf:type     ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "NVIDIA Cosmos3-Nano" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:description  "16B-parameter omnimodal world foundation model for Physical AI. Generates and reasons over video, images, audio, and robot actions. OpenMDW 1.1 license (commercial use). Requires NVIDIA GPU (Ampere/Hopper/Blackwell), BF16 precision, Linux. Potential uses: generate preview animations from entity descriptions, 3D scene understanding for graph visualization, multimodal graph ingest (video/image/audio sources). Shares NVIDIA GPU sidecar infrastructure with NeMo Speech." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:nemo-speech ;
               kpred:open-question "Massive resource requirements (16B params, BF16) — viable only for users with high-end NVIDIA GPUs. Evaluate smaller distilled variants when available." ;
               kpred:open-question "Integration path: same Python sidecar as NeMo Speech? Separate container? Which Cosmos capabilities map to graph workflows (video→triples, entity→animation)?" .

# The two-way local folder sync is done; these are the planned next steps for it.
kb:drive-folder-sync rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Google Drive folder sync" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F56" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "Sync the workspace to a (shareable) Google Drive folder — the cloud sibling of local folder sync. Two-way: push each KB out as {name}.ttl and pull .ttl files back, reconciling new graphs and updating changed ones through the SHARED kb-import reconcile (src/lib/stores/kb-import.ts, extracted so local + Drive sync behave identically), with a content-hash loop guard. Uses the drive.file OAuth scope (only app-owned files). Store: src/lib/stores/drive-sync.svelte.ts; Drive folder ops (ensureFolder/listFolderTurtles/uploadTurtleToFolder) added to integrations/google/drive.ts; controls in the graph menu's graph-package panel (☁ sync to Google Drive / resync / unlink / auto-sync). Auto-sync (opt-in): debounced auto-push on every KB mutation (hooked into kb.svelte alongside the local export) + ~45s background poll for cloud pulls, with silent token refresh (bails instead of popping a consent dialog on a timer). Binary sidecar assets (preview blobs, GLB models, icon blobs) round-trip too — pushed into a shared Drive assets/ subfolder with KB-scoped filenames ({stem}__{category}__{file}) and pulled back via the TTL's asset refs. Feature-complete for graphs + assets; further polish (per-KB Drive subfolders, conflict UI) is optional." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:workspace-sync ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:google-drive-sync ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/stores/__tests__/drive-sync.test.ts" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:workspace-index .

kb:workspace-index rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Workspace index + session recovery" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F57" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:description  "A top-level index .ttl at the workspace root that references every synced graph and sidecar file (local OR cloud) in Turtle form — a manifest of the folder's contents. With it, a Reckons.AI browser session and a set of synced files (local folder or Google Drive) can recover the FILE SESSION: reopen exactly the graphs, assets, and view that were active, rather than re-linking each graph by hand. The index is itself a graph (files/graphs as entities with paths, stable IDs, last-synced timestamps), so it round-trips like everything else and stays diffable." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:workspace-sync ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:drive-folder-sync .

kb:visual-workflow-harness rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Visual Workflow Harness (F42/F43)" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:visual-testing ;
               kpred:description  "Workflow-level visual testing decoupled from Storybook (playwright.workflows.config.ts). A device-matrix harness (tests/visual/workflow-harness.ts: useDevice / screenshotStep / stepAudit) with a navigation-sweep exemplar auditing overflow + sub-44px touch targets across 5 devices. Two offline (local-VLM, no cloud) tools: scripts/visual-graph.ts turns the screenshot matrix into a browsable review-graph TTL (TestStep nodes + hnav tour + hover previews), and scripts/offline/visual-diff.ts (vision-vlm diffImagesVLM) diff-detects regressions between two deploys and queues each as a pending question. npm run test:workflows / visual:graph / offline:visual-diff." ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/visual/user-stories/navigation-sweep.test.ts" .

