               kpred:open-question "Which tasks are safe to move to local-by-default without hurting quality (measure against the comparison bench)? A single 'maximize local' toggle vs. per-task control?" .

# -- Work Tiering (F74.3) -------------------------------------------------------
# The routing rule for HOW work gets done, not what. Offloading to a local model
# is not free: a local job that emits 30 findings of which 25 are noise MOVES cost
# from generation to triage rather than removing it. Deterministic checks have zero
# triage cost because they are right by construction — so the token budget is served
# better by growing the SCRIPT tier than the AGENT tier.

kb:work-tiering rdf:type       ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Work tiering (script · local agent · Opus)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F74.3" ;
               kpred:has-status   "in-progress" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:aggressive-local-offload ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:offline-align-review ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:session-tokens ;
               kpred:description  "Every recurring task is routed to the cheapest tier that can do it correctly, decided by the first test it passes: (1) SCRIPT — the answer is checkable by a rule (does this path exist, does this parse, is this status in the enum), so it is deterministic code, zero tokens, zero hallucination, runs in CI and fails loudly; (2) LOCAL AGENT — the answer is judgment over language and being wrong is cheap because the output is a PROPOSAL a human gates (first-pass code review, description drafting, staleness reads), always emitted to knowledge.pending.jsonl, never to source; (3) OPUS — cross-file architectural reasoning, deciding the process, triaging the queue the other tiers fill, and writing code that lands. Opus designs the harness; the local model is a plugin inside it (ground -> prompt -> validate -> emit-proposal, per the PR #43 devstral salvage). Promotion ladder: anything Opus does twice becomes an agent job or a script; anything an agent gets right RELIABLY is demoted to a script, because reliability proves the rule was expressible." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Grow the script tier: graph-lint (dead has-file/tested-by links, status enum, feature-id collisions, dangling depends-on) + convention lint (ETHICS_PREAMBLE presence, CSS vars, americanize --check) + pending.jsonl schema/dedupe validation." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Agent tier: local description drafting for entities whose kpred:description is missing or stale vs the code." ;
               kpred:measured     "Tracked by npm run session:tokens (kb:session-tokens) — the metric that says whether a tier move actually saved anything." ;
               kpred:has-tier     kb:tier-script ;
               kpred:has-tier     kb:tier-local-agent ;
               kpred:has-tier     kb:tier-claude-code .

# The three tiers as first-class entities, so the PROCESS is queryable from the graph
# rather than only prose in CLAUDE.md. Routing takes the first tier whose
# kpred:admits-when test the task passes, cheapest first.

kb:tier-script rdf:type        ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "Tier 1 — deterministic script" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:work-tiering ;
               hnav:order   1 ;
               kpred:admits-when  "The answer is checkable by a rule: does this path exist, does this parse, is this value in the enum, are these two files in sync." ;
               kpred:cost         "zero tokens, zero triage — right by construction" ;
               kpred:runs-on      "any machine; runs in CI as of 2026-07-14 (ci.yml script-tier job), ADVISORY — see kb:tier-script-ci" ;
               kpred:emits        "a pass/fail exit code, and optionally pending findings" ;
               kpred:exemplar     "scripts/offline/graph-lint.ts" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "Until 2026-07-14 this entity claimed the tier 'runs in CI and fails loudly'. It ran in CI nowhere: only safety-attestation was wired, so graph-lint, status-evidence, prompt-audit and alignment-sweep executed only when someone remembered to run them locally — and when nobody did, the work fell to Opus at cloud rates. A free tier that no trigger invokes displaces no tokens. The CI half is now true; the FAIL-LOUDLY half is not yet (advisory only, kb:tier-script-ci)." ;
               kpred:description  "The default and preferred tier. Deterministic code with no model in the loop, so it can run in CI. Prefer growing this tier over the agent tier: a check that is right by construction costs nothing to triage, whereas a noisy model job merely moves cost from generation to review." .

# The gate is not on yet, and the graph says so rather than implying otherwise.
kb:tier-script-ci rdf:type     ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Script tier in CI — blocking" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:work-tiering ;
               hnav:order   4 ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "The script tier runs on every push/PR (ci.yml, job `script-tier`) and FAILS the build when a job marked blocking:true fails. jobs.json carries the `blocking` flag; run-all.ts has a `--ci` mode that exits non-zero. Blocking today: published-graph-guard (static/knowledge.ttl IS the public graph — the one failure you cannot take back once pushed) and build-guard (a dev-mode artifact must never deploy). Everything else reports and queues findings without gating, because a diagnostic that fails the build on every finding gets switched off, and then it protects nothing." ;
               kpred:correction   "CORRECTED 2026-07-14, and the correction is the lesson. This shipped ADVISORY for one day because published-graph-guard reported '166 test-harness terms' in the published graph. THE FINDING WAS FALSE: the guard banned `urn:reckons:story/`, which is the PRODUCT'S OWN guided-story vocabulary (src/lib/rdf/story.ts, used by the landing page and TurtleChatPanel, declared in reckons-production.ttl). The real harness namespace is `urn:reckons:test/`, and it appears ZERO times. The published graph was clean the entire time. An unverified finding, believed and repeated across three commit messages, kept a real gate switched off — an unverifiable claim treated as evidence, which is the exact failure this product exists to refuse. We committed it against ourselves." ;
               kpred:principle    "A finding is a CLAIM. A tool that reports a violation is a party with an interest in having found one. Verify the finding before you act on it — especially when acting on it means weakening a control." .

kb:tier-local-agent rdf:type   ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "Tier 2 — local model agent" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:work-tiering ;
               hnav:order   2 ;
               kpred:admits-when  "The answer is judgment over language, AND being wrong is cheap because the output is a proposal a human gates. Drafting a description, first-pass code review, staleness reads." ;
               kpred:cost         "zero cloud tokens; local GPU time; nonzero TRIAGE cost — this is the tier's real price" ;
               kpred:runs-on      "a machine with Ollama and a model that fits in local VRAM (opt-in via OLLAMA_BASE_URL)" ;
               kpred:emits        "PROPOSALS ONLY — pending entries in knowledge.pending.jsonl, never an edit to source or TTL" ;
               kpred:exemplar     "scripts/offline/describe-entities.ts" ;
               kpred:harness      "ground -> prompt -> validate -> emit-proposal. The model never runs free: the script grounds it in the graph, constrains the prompt, validates the output (rejecting hedges, placeholders, and invented file paths), and emits a reviewable proposal. Local models hallucinate conventions and mangle serialization (PR #43 devstral salvage), so the harness — not the model — is the deliverable." ;
               kpred:description  "A local Ollama model fills a judgment hole inside a scripted harness. Because output is always a gated proposal, a wrong answer costs a click in the Review tab rather than a bad commit." .

kb:tier-claude-code rdf:type   ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "Tier 3 — Claude Code (Opus)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:work-tiering ;
               hnav:order   3 ;
               kpred:admits-when  "The task exceeds local hardware, or needs cross-file architectural reasoning, or decides process, or writes code that lands." ;
               kpred:cost         "cloud/session tokens — the scarce resource the other two tiers exist to protect" ;
               kpred:runs-on      "Anthropic cloud; no local hardware ceiling" ;
               kpred:emits        "code that lands, plan/TTL edits, and triage decisions on the queue the other tiers fill" ;
               kpred:description  "Some work stays here permanently and that is correct — it is not a failure to offload. The binding constraint is HARDWARE: local models are capped by VRAM (this workstation tops out around a 33B model at Q4), so long-context synthesis across many files, high-fidelity vision, and frontier-quality coding judgment have no local equivalent. Claude Code also OWNS the process: it designs the harnesses the other two tiers run inside, decides the routing, and reviews their output. Delegation is downward-only — Opus decides, the lower tiers execute." ;
               kpred:stays-here   "Architecture and design decisions; roadmap/TTL plan edits; triaging pending proposals; writing the script- and agent-tier harnesses themselves; any change that lands in main." ;
               kpred:hardware-bound "Long-context synthesis (>32k of cross-file context); frontier coding judgment; final review of a local model's proposals. Local VRAM ceiling makes these infeasible offline, so they are NOT candidates for demotion." .

kb:session-tokens rdf:type     ktype:Feature ;
               kpred:test-coverage "none" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "No automated test covers this feature (audited 2026-07-12, scripts/offline/status-evidence.ts). The status is still accurate — it IS shipped and in use; test coverage and deployment maturity are orthogonal, and pretending otherwise would be its own dishonesty. This is a declared RISK, not a hidden one: kb:honest-status requires the gap be visible rather than silent." ;
               rdfs:label   "Session token metric" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F74.4" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:aggressive-local-offload ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:cost-awareness ;
               kpred:description  "Makes local-offload measurable instead of assumed. scripts/session-tokens.ts parses this project's Claude Code transcripts (~/.claude/projects/<slug>/*.jsonl) into per-session token usage: run it before and after moving grunt work to a lower tier and watch the fresh-input + output lines drop. A weighted column (input + 1.25*cacheWrite + 0.1*cacheRead + 5*output, rough Opus ratios) ranks sessions by real consumption, and 'no-cache burn' sessions (lots of fresh input, little cache reuse) are flagged as the expensive pattern to avoid — cache-read is the cheap tier, so long cache-warm sessions are fine. Run: npm run session:tokens [-- --top=N] [--path=<dir>]." ;
               kpred:done         "scripts/session-tokens.ts; npm run session:tokens." .

# -- RDF Dataset Migration: Turtle -> TriG (F75) ---------------------------------
# src/lib/rdf/types.ts opens by declaring the model: "a personal knowledge base is a
# set of n-quads" where g carries provenance. But Turtle is a TRIPLES-ONLY format --
# it cannot express the 4th element -- so every static/*.ttl silently drops g, and
# import-ttl.ts assigns every imported triple one synthetic graph. The documentation
# KBs are the only graphs in the system with no provenance, confidence, or review
# status: second-class citizens in their own data model.

kb:rdf-dataset-migration rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "RDF dataset capability (TriG-tolerant readers, Turtle on disk)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F75" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:work-tiering ;
               kpred:description  "Honor the n-quad model (src/lib/rdf/types.ts: 'a knowledge base is a set of n-quads', g = provenance) WITHOUT giving up Turtle's editability. TriG is a strict superset of Turtle — every .ttl is already legal TriG — but the superset runs ONE WAY: serializing back to Turtle/N-Triples silently drops the graph term. Verified with N3: reckons-roadmap.ttl parses identically under format 'TriG' (1526 quads, all default-graph), while the Turtle parser rejects a named graph outright. DECISION (2026-07-12): make every READER TriG-format (accepts both, zero behavior change) but keep the hand-authored KBs as default-graph .ttl. Rationale: default-graph Turtle concatenates textually and every triple lands in one place, so combining and editing graphs stays trivial; named graphs would make a merge semantic rather than textual. The .trig extension is reserved for files that genuinely need named graphs — the EXTENSION IS A CONTRACT, so a .ttl containing a graph block would be a lie that breaks any format:'Turtle' consumer." ;
               kpred:done         "Readers switched to format 'TriG' (import-ttl.ts, multi-graph-parse.ts, mcp-server/kb-reader.ts) — zero behavior change, 383 RDF tests green, since every .ttl is already legal TriG." ;
               kpred:done         "toTriG (src/lib/rdf/serialize.ts) — one named graph per SOURCE, lossless. Round-trip tested: parse our own output and every fact still knows which source it came from. A companion test PINS THE LOSS in toTurtle (its output round-trips with everything in the default graph), so nobody mistakes it for a lossless export." ;
               kpred:measured     "18 of 19 repo .ttl files declare 0-1 sources, so a named graph carries ZERO information for them — they stay .ttl forever. TriG earns its place at EXPORT, not in the repo: today toTurtle drops g, so after ingesting 5 PDFs and exporting, 'where did this fact come from?' is unanswerable." ;
               kpred:decided      "THE GRAPH TERM IS THE SOURCE — not the KB. TriG has ONE graph slot; spending it on KB-bundling would silently destroy per-source provenance. File = KB, named graph = source. Bundle multiple KBs with a graph package (which also carries assets, as TriG cannot)." ;
               kpred:refined      "SUPERSEDED IN SCOPE by kb:ttl-trig-split (Matt, 2026-07-13). The question 'what does g mean?' was the wrong question, because it assumed one answer for one product. It has TWO answers, because there are two products. PRIVATE (.ttl): g means almost nothing — a source the user controls and can rewrite is self-attestation, not evidence, and a private graph needs no provenance because it makes no claim on anybody. PUBLISHED (.trig): g is a PUBLICATION — facts attributed to an accountable publisher, at a time, under a policy. THAT is what turns a source into provenance, because a publisher can be checked, cited, disputed and held responsible, and a private file cannot. So the format split is not a serialization preference; it is the boundary between the individual product and the institutional one." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Wire toTriG into the export UI; adopt .trig per-file only when a KB genuinely carries >1 source. OPEN (asked): whether a pure-text multi-KB meta-file is wanted enough to overload the graph term." ;
               kpred:decided      "TRIG IN, TURTLE OUT (2026-07-12). Readers accept TriG; files stay .ttl with a default graph; a KB becomes .trig only when it genuinely has more than one source. Justified by kb:provenance-model below — not a marketing compromise: for a single-source graph a named graph is ceremony carrying zero information, so default-graph Turtle is the CORRECT model, and 'your data is a plain .ttl file' stays true for the overwhelming majority of cases." ;
               kpred:bug          "toTurtle()'s provenance block is ORPHANED: it emits <urn:kbase:stmt/{id}> prov:wasDerivedFrom <source>, but the triples above carry no statement id and there is no rdf:Statement reification linking stmt/{id} back to its (s,p,o). The block is therefore unrecoverable decoration — it costs bytes and conveys nothing. toTurtleFull (proper reification) and toNQuads (native quads) are correct; plain toTurtle is the lossy path and must say so." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:provenance-model .

# -- Provenance model: when is a named graph worth it? ---------------------------
# Raised 2026-07-12: "user-supplied info has no source, so the quad's 4th element is
# a fiction anyway." Half right, and the half that is wrong matters.
#
# The source of a manually-typed fact is NOT undefined — it is THE USER, which is the
# highest-trust source in the system (Source.trustLevel 'trusted' auto-confirms). What
# is undefined is the EXTERNAL source. The single most valuable provenance distinction
# in Reckons.AI is human-asserted vs machine-extracted — "I know this" vs "a 3B model
# guessed this from a PDF" — and that is exactly what g encodes. Discarding it because
# "manual has no source" would throw away the most useful provenance we have.
#
# But the CONCLUSION still holds, for a different reason: a named graph earns its keep
# only when a graph has MORE THAN ONE source.

kb:provenance-model rdf:type   ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "Provenance model (when a named graph earns its keep)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:rdf-dataset-migration ;
               kpred:description  "A named graph carries information only when a KB has multiple sources. SINGLE-SOURCE graphs (the hand-authored static/*.ttl docs KBs — their one source IS the file) gain nothing from a graph term: default-graph Turtle is the correct model, not a compromise. MULTI-SOURCE graphs (an ingested user KB mixing three PDFs, a repo, two URLs, and the user's own typing) make g load-bearing, and dropping it destroys real information. Hence: TriG in, Turtle out, .trig only on genuine multi-source." ;
               kpred:principle    "The source of manual input is the USER — the highest-trust source in the system — not 'nothing'. Human-asserted vs machine-extracted is the provenance distinction that actually pays rent." ;
               kpred:principle    "A named graph on a single-source KB is ceremony carrying zero information. Ceremony that conveys nothing is cost without benefit." .

kb:rdf-vocabulary-hygiene rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "RDF vocabulary hygiene" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F75.1" ;
               kpred:has-status   "in-progress" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "in-progress means DETECTED, not FIXED (2026-07-12). graph-lint now catches every defect class below, but ZERO of the defects are repaired: the 3 duplicate feature-ids, 6 dangling refs, 4 dead has-file links, the kb:design-system IRI collision, the prefix aliasing, the untyped numerics, and urn:reckons:leap all still stand. The lint fails on them today, by design. (kb:honest-status)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:rdf-dataset-migration ;
               kpred:description  "Defects found by the 2026-07-12 spec audit. Turtle CONFORMANCE is fine (all 19 graphs parse under N3, the reference parser; 353 RDF tests green including a W3C suite) — the problems are semantic. (a) kb:design-system is one IRI naming two different things: a ktype:Concept (fonts/colors/components) and a ktype:Feature (the shadcn migration), with two labels and two conflicting statuses, so RDF merges them into one contradictory entity. (b) urn:kbase:predicate/ is bound to THREE prefix names (kpred:, pred:, p:) and urn:kbase:meta/ to two, and the app's DEFAULT_PREFIXES exports pred:/meta: while every hand-authored TTL uses kpred:/kmeta:. (c) 15 cardinality violations — single-valued predicates repeated on one subject. (d) kpred:order, kpred:pace, kpred:test-count are untyped strings where 95 other integers are xsd:integer, so they sort lexically ('10' < '9'). (e) urn:reckons:leap is used as a predicate but has no / or # separator, so it cannot be prefix-shortened and defeats the PREDICATE_PREFIX convention that decides whether a predicate renders as a graph edge. Each defect class gets a graph-lint check so it cannot recur." ;
               kpred:open-question "urn:kbase: is not a registered URN namespace (RFC 8141 requires a registered NID). It is a syntactically valid IRI so Turtle accepts it, but it is neither conformant nor dereferenceable. Migrate to https://reckons.ai/kb/ — worth the churn?" .

kb:feature-lifecycle-vocab rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Feature lifecycle as a SKOS vocabulary" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F75.2" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "Status corrected planned<-in-progress (2026-07-12): NONE of this is built. No SKOS scheme exists; kpred:has-status is still a free-text literal everywhere. Decided, not started. (kb:honest-status)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:rdf-dataset-migration ;
               kpred:description  "kpred:has-status carried a free-text literal, which is how 'pending -> confirmed/rejected/refined' ended up in a feature's status slot. The lifecycle is a CLOSED vocabulary, so it is modeled as one: ktype:status/* skos:Concepts in the ktype:FeatureLifecycle scheme, ordered by hnav:order, referenced as IRIs rather than strings. This makes the lifecycle queryable (ask the graph for the stages, in order) instead of tacit, and makes an invalid status a broken reference that graph-lint catches structurally." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:rdf-vocabulary-hygiene .

# -- Bring-Your-Own Host: publish a static site in a handful of steps (F76) -------
# The other half of Option C (kb:adult-content-policy). We tell the user "export it
# and host it yourself" — and that is a BRUSH-OFF if self-hosting is a weekend of DNS
# and CI config, but a genuine, dignified option if it is a handful of steps. Making
# publishing easy is what makes the refusal-to-carry policy humane instead of hostile.
#
# It is also the same sentence as the policy itself: we are not a registrar and not a
# host, and we decline to be the intermediary — while removing every obstacle to the
# user being their own. GitHub Pages, Netlify, Cloudflare Pages and others are FREE.
# Reckons.AI's job is to make the corpus, the portfolio, or the blog fall out of the
# graph and land on the host of the user's choosing, with no lock-in and no account
# with us.

# -- Decision record: 2026-07-12 safety + tiering + RDF session ------------------
# Compacted index of the decisions taken this session, so a future session can find
# them without re-deriving. Each decision's full reasoning lives on the entity named.

# -- Honest status (standing principle, 2026-07-12) ------------------------------
# Caught in the act: SAFETY.md was written stating the publish gate in the PRESENT
# TENSE ("we gate", "we refuse") while F66 is merely PLANNED — publishing is in fact
# ungated today. The same document also claimed the ethics preamble "cannot be
# overridden", when it is open-source client code anyone can delete. Both were fixed.
# The lesson is cheap to state and expensive to forget: a safety document that
# overclaims is worse than no document, because it converts a gap into a lie.

kb:honest-status rdf:type      ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "Honest status — always describe the current state truthfully" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:reckons-ai ;
               kpred:description  "Every user-facing, legal, and internal document must distinguish WHAT IS BUILT from WHAT IS INTENDED, at the point of each claim — not in a footnote. Aspiration written in the present tense is a lie with good manners. This applies hardest to SAFETY.md, COUNSEL-BRIEF.md, and any status shown in the app: overclaiming a control we cannot exercise is itself a liability (and it is the specific failure the 2026-07-12 session committed and then corrected). It also applies to the roadmap: kpred:has-status must reflect reality, and a feature is not 'functional' because we wish it were." ;
               kpred:principle    "Never describe a control we do not have. If a gate is planned, say PLANNED — in the sentence that mentions the gate." ;
               kpred:principle    "Report failures as loudly as successes. The safety attestation records its own failing control on purpose: a log that only records success is worthless as evidence, and a status that is always green is not a status." ;
               kpred:principle    "Say the weakness out loud. The content classifier matches descriptions of content rather than content, so SAFETY.md says exactly that, in the section that describes the classifier." ;
               kpred:enforced-by  "scripts/offline/safety-attestation.ts (verifies controls against the live code rather than asserting them); scripts/offline/graph-lint.ts (a feature cannot ship ahead of its own gate)." .

kb:session-2026-07-12 rdf:type ktype:Decision ;
               rdfs:label   "Decisions — 2026-07-12 (work tiering · RDF format · safety policy)" ;
               kpred:decided-on   "2026-07-12"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:decision     "WORK TIERING (kb:work-tiering, F74.3): route every recurring task to the cheapest tier that can do it correctly — script (rule-checkable, zero tokens, zero triage) > local agent (judgment over language, proposals only, inside a ground/prompt/validate/emit harness) > Claude Code (hardware-bound, cross-file reasoning, decides process, writes code that lands). Offloading is NOT free: a noisy local job moves cost from generation to triage. Prefer growing the SCRIPT tier. Promotion ladder: what Opus does twice becomes a job; what an agent gets right reliably becomes a script." ;
               kpred:decision     "RDF FORMAT (kb:rdf-dataset-migration, F75): TriG in, Turtle out. Readers accept TriG (done); files stay .ttl with a default graph; .trig only when a KB genuinely carries >1 source. Grounded in kb:provenance-model — a named graph on a single-source KB is ceremony carrying zero information." ;
               kpred:decision     "EGRESS (kb:data-egress-model): export is a RIGHT, distribution is a PRIVILEGE. Plain-text export of the user's own graph is never blocked; gates apply only where Reckons.AI is the intermediary carrying content to someone else. graph-lint enforces BOTH directions." ;
               kpred:decision     "ADULT CONTENT — OPTION C (kb:adult-content-policy, F66.1): gate only what we carry. No mediated distribution channel for adult content; authoring, storage and export unimpeded. Deletes the gameable attestation entirely — context is never an input to the gate, so there is nothing to lie about. No accounts, no server, no PII, no age-verification surface." ;
               kpred:decision     "SAFETY RECORD (scripts/offline/safety-attestation.ts): the app can retain no evidence about USERS (no server, no accounts, no logs), so it retains verified evidence about the SOFTWARE — a dated, git-chained, weekly attestation that the good-faith controls exist and still pass. Records failures deliberately; a log that only records success is worthless as evidence." ;
               kpred:decision     "PUBLISHING (kb:byo-static-host, F76): never a registrar, never a host. Ease of self-hosting is a SAFETY-POLICY dependency — 'export it and self-host' is only a fair answer if self-hosting is genuinely easy." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:work-tiering ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:rdf-dataset-migration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:adult-content-policy ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:byo-static-host ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:data-egress-model ;
               kpred:artifact     "COUNSEL-BRIEF.md — engineering brief for Data Insight Solutions LLC's counsel: what the software sees (nothing), what it controls (best-effort, bypassable by design), the tiers, and the surviving question (does 18 U.S.C. 2258A attach to a tool that hosts nothing?)." .

kb:byo-static-host rdf:type    ktype:Feature ;
               kpred:show-on-landing "true" ;
               kpred:landing-label   "Bring-your-own host" ;
               kpred:landing-note    "Publish a corpus, portfolio, or blog to GitHub Pages, Netlify or Cloudflare — free, yours, no lock-in" ;
               rdfs:label   "Bring-your-own static host (publish in a handful of steps)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F76" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:docs-pipeline ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:adult-content-policy ;
               kpred:data-egress  "user-export" ;
               kpred:description  "Turn a graph into a deployable static site and hand it to whichever free host the user already has — GitHub Pages, Netlify, Cloudflare Pages, Vercel, or a plain folder they drag anywhere. Reckons.AI is NOT a domain registrar and NOT a file host, and never will be: it generates the artifact and gets out of the way. Target: a handful of steps from graph to live URL. Three shapes must work equally well — a complicated corpus of information (docs/wiki, the F27.2 pipeline already does this), a portfolio of visual art (asset-heavy, F74 asset viewer), and a blog (chronological WebPage nodes). All three are the SAME machinery: WebPage entities in the graph -> content/*.md -> a static build. The host is a swappable target, not a dependency." ;
               kpred:principle    "No registrar, no hosting, no accounts, no lock-in. The user's site lives on the user's host under the user's name. We remove obstacles to self-hosting; we do not become the host." ;
               kpred:principle    "This is what makes Option C fair. 'Export it and self-host it' is only a real answer if self-hosting is genuinely easy — so ease of publishing is a SAFETY-POLICY dependency, not just a convenience feature." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Host adapters (GitHub Pages / Netlify / Cloudflare / plain zip); a guided publish flow; per-shape templates (corpus · portfolio · blog); a preflight that runs the F66 gate before handing the artifact over." ;
               kpred:open-question "How far do we go into the host's setup? A generated GitHub Action + a 'Deploy' button is a handful of steps; an OAuth app that pushes for them is fewer steps but makes us a mediated-distribution path (see kb:data-egress-model) and would pull the F66 gate into a flow we would rather keep as pure user-export. Where exactly is the line?" .

# -- F80: Async Orchestration — the user is the bottleneck, so remove them from it ----
# The current loop is synchronous and it wastes the scarcest resource in the system:
# the agent finishes a slice, writes a summary into chat, and BLOCKS until Matt reads it
# and answers. Matt is AFK most of the time. Work stops for hours on a question that
# takes him ten seconds.
#
# Invert it. The agent does not ask Matt — it asks THE GRAPH, and keeps going.
# Reckons.AI already has every piece of this (F32 partial facts): a triple with no object
# becomes needsObject:true with object '?', the Review tab shows an entity picker instead
# of accept/reject, and recordAnswer() writes the answer to knowledge.answers.jsonl where
# a polling agent picks it up. The substrate is BUILT. What is missing is the agent side
# of it, a model of what a question BLOCKS, and a report that accumulates instead of
# interrupting.
#
# This is also the sharpest possible dogfooding: the coordination layer for building
# Reckons.AI becomes Reckons.AI.

# -- F91: Question router — throw a question to the graph most likely to answer it ----
#
# F80 taught an agent to ASK THE GRAPH instead of blocking the human, WITHIN one graph. F91 is
# the outward version: a question the local graph cannot answer is ROUTED to the graph(s) most
# RELATED to it — the ones whose knowledge overlaps the question's subject. "WHO, in the world,
# could answer this?" becomes a computed ranking, not a guess.
#
# THROW AND FORGET. The asker does not wait. It emits the question, the router addresses it to
# the best-related graphs, and the answer flows back whenever it arrives (the F80 answer-loop,
# across graphs rather than within one). Decision-making does not stall on reachability.
#
# ACROSS ENTERPRISE BOUNDARIES, this DAISY-CHAINS under RBAC (F84). A proposed Reckoning is not
# public — it is a private deliberation gathering the facts it needs — so a question cannot be
# broadcast. It hops graph to graph along ALLOWED edges only: graph A asks graph B; if B cannot
# answer but is related to C and the policy permits, B forwards it. Each hop is authorized, each
# hop records provenance, and the answer returns along the chain it came.

kb:question-router rdf:type    ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Question router (throw a question to whoever can answer it)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F91" ;
               kpred:has-status   "in-progress" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "in-progress (2026-07-15): phase 1 scaffolded, phase 2 (throw-and-forget) functional — the local answer-return loop closes with opt-in consent and external-graph provenance. NOT done: a UI to set consent, real cross-boundary transport, and phase 3 RBAC (gated on F84). One process's pending queue stands in for two graphs today." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:async-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:publisher-subscriptions ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:cross-kb-alignment ;
               kpred:description  "A question the local graph cannot settle is addressed OUTWARD, to the graphs most related to its subject. Relatedness is computed (shared entities, shared predicates, subject overlap) so 'who could answer this?' is a ranking, not a hunch. The asker throws and forgets; the answer returns asynchronously along the F80 answer-loop, extended across graphs. Across enterprise boundaries it daisy-chains under RBAC: each hop is an ALLOWED edge, authorized and provenance-stamped, because a proposed Reckoning is a private deliberation, not a broadcast." ;
               kpred:principle    "A question is addressed by RELATEDNESS, not by broadcast. Sending every question to every graph is spam and a privacy leak; sending it to the graph whose knowledge overlaps the subject is routing. The router's whole value is picking WHO." ;
               kpred:principle    "THROW AND FORGET. Decision-making must not stall on whether the answerer is reachable right now. The question is durable (a partial fact); the answer arrives when it arrives; the asker never blocks." ;
               kpred:principle    "DAISY-CHAIN ONLY ALONG ALLOWED EDGES. A non-public Reckoning gathers its facts privately. A hop that policy does not permit does not happen — a question must never leak to a graph its owner did not authorize. RBAC is the routing table, not an afterthought." ;
               kpred:principle    "Every hop records provenance. A question that arrived via A→B→C carries that chain, and the answer returns along it. Provenance is an accountability relation (the thesis): you must be able to say WHERE a gathered fact came from and by whose leave." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:async-orchestration ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:cross-kb-alignment ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:qr-relevance ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:qr-throw-forget ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:qr-rbac-chain .

kb:qr-relevance rdf:type       ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 1 — rank which graphs are most related to a question" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:question-router ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/question-router.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/question-router.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "routeQuestion(question, graphs) ranks candidates by relatedness (knows-the-subject strongest, then predicate familiarity, then neighbourhood overlap); addressees() thresholds so we route rather than broadcast. 7 tests: the graph that already knows the subject ranks first, a graph with no overlap is never addressed, neighbourhood overlap works when the exact subject is absent. NOT yet wired into the review/reckoning UI — that is the remaining work." ;
               hnav:order   1 ;
               kpred:description  "Given a question (subject + predicate, object open) and a set of candidate graphs, score each by how RELATED it is to the question: does it contain the subject entity, entities that align to it (cross-kb-align), or heavy use of the question's predicate? Output a ranking — the deterministic core of 'who could answer this'. Script tier: the relatedness signals are countable, no model required for the first cut; embeddings refine it later." ;
               kpred:remaining    "src/lib/rdf/question-router.ts: score(question, graphs) -> ranked candidates; tests; expose in the review/reckoning UI as 'ask another graph'." .

kb:qr-throw-forget rdf:type    ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 2 — throw the question, resume on the answer" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:question-router ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/agent/route-question.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/agent/return-answer.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/question-router-reach.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "The local loop closes end to end. route-question.ts runs the relevance router and THROWS the question to the top-related graph via ask.ts — but now (a) only to graphs that OPTED IN (kpred:answers-questions \"true\"): reach by consent, not by relatedness, so a graph that never said 'you may ask me' is never addressed however related; and (b) stamped with a RETURN ADDRESS (askedByGraph = the origin that could not answer). return-answer.ts correlates each new answer back to its routed question and delivers it to the ORIGIN graph's pending queue as an external-graph fact (answered-by-graph + hop-chain [origin, answerer]), always reviewed, never machine-settled (F88 competentGate('external-graph')='user' — another party's claim, the thesis applied to federated answers). 31 tests pass (router + reach + verifiability). OUTSTANDING: this is one PROCESS's queue standing in for two graphs — real cross-boundary transport (decided: reuse n8n + pub-sub, later) and the RBAC per-hop authorization (phase 3, gated on F84) are not built. The consent marker is honoured but there is no UI to SET it yet." ;
               hnav:order   2 ;
               kpred:description  "Emit the question to the top-ranked graph(s) that opted in, as a partial fact carrying a return address (askedByGraph). The existing F80 answer-loop, extended by return-answer.ts, carries the reply back to the ORIGIN graph as a reviewable external-graph claim. The asker never waits. Reuses ask.ts / answers.ts." ;
               kpred:decided      "Reach = subscribed + opt-in (kpred:answers-questions). Transport = reuse n8n + pub-sub, later. Answers = pending + provenance, ALWAYS reviewed (external-graph is never machine-settled). RBAC = finish the local loop first, F84 later. (Matt, 2026-07-15.)" ;
               kpred:remaining    "A UI to SET the opt-in consent marker; real cross-process/cross-boundary transport (n8n + pub-sub); the 'ask another graph' review-UI entry (shared with phase 1)." .

kb:qr-rbac-chain rdf:type      ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 3 — daisy-chain under RBAC, with provenance per hop" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:question-router ;
               hnav:order   3 ;
               kpred:description  "The enterprise case. A question hops graph to graph along edges RBAC permits: if the best-related graph cannot answer but is related to another the policy allows, it forwards. Each hop authorizes, records who forwarded to whom, and the answer returns along the chain. Depends on the TriG enterprise overlay (F84) for the RBAC/provenance model. A proposed Reckoning gathers its facts this way — privately, accountably, and never by broadcast." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:trig-enterprise-overlay ;
               kpred:remaining    "kpred:hop-chain provenance; policy check per hop; forward-if-allowed; return-along-chain. Gated on F84." .

kb:async-orchestration rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Async orchestration (agents ask the graph, not the human)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F80" ;
               kpred:has-status   "in-progress" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "Corrected 2026-07-14: this said `planned` while phases 1 and 3 were already SHIPPED and passing 15 tests (scripts/agent/ask.ts, answers.ts, digest.ts — used daily). kb:honest-status cuts BOTH ways: a roadmap that understates is still a roadmap you cannot trust, and it was about to be the source for public marketing copy. Still genuinely outstanding: phase 2 (blocked-vs-unblocked work) and phase 4 (the visual test of the ask/answer loop)." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:partial-facts ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:work-tiering ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:review-workbench ;
               kpred:description  "Agents stop blocking on the human. When an agent needs a decision it EMITS A QUESTION AS A PARTIAL FACT (subject + predicate known, object '?') into knowledge.pending.jsonl, tags the work that question blocks, and moves to the next unblocked task. Matt answers whenever he likes — in the Review tab's entity picker, in Shelly chat, or by editing the triple directly — and recordAnswer() flows it back via knowledge.answers.jsonl, where the waiting agent resumes. Findings accumulate into a ROLLING DIGEST entity in the graph rather than a chat summary per task, so an AFK session produces one report that grew, not twenty that interrupted. The user becomes asynchronous; the pipeline never stalls on them." ;
               kpred:principle    "The user is the bottleneck. Do not make them a blocking call." ;
               kpred:principle    "An agent that cannot proceed should ASK THE GRAPH and pick up different work — never idle, never guess. A guess silently entered into a knowledge graph is worse than a stalled task." ;
               kpred:principle    "Reckons.AI is the sounding board, not the chat window. A question left as a partial fact is reviewable, mergeable, searchable and dated. A question asked in chat is gone when the session ends." ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:async-ask ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:async-unblock ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:async-digest ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:async-visual-test ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:partial-facts .

kb:async-ask rdf:type          ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 1 — agents ask the graph" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:async-orchestration ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "scripts/agent/__tests__/async-loop.test.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/agent/ask.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/agent/answers.ts" ;
               hnav:order   1 ;
               kpred:description  "An agent-side library + CLI (scripts/agent/) so asking is one call, not hand-rolled JSONL. ask() emits a partial fact (question, agent, priority, and the task it blocks). answers() polls knowledge.answers.jsonl and returns what has been resolved since a cursor. Deliberately a SCRIPT-tier primitive: deterministic, no model, usable by the local Ollama tier and by Claude Code alike." ;
               kpred:remaining    "scripts/agent/ask.ts (emit question); scripts/agent/answers.ts (poll + cursor); npm run agent:ask / agent:answers." .

kb:async-unblock rdf:type      ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 2 — blocked vs unblocked work" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:async-orchestration ;
               hnav:order   2 ;
               kpred:description  "A question declares what it blocks (kpred:blocks -> a roadmap entity or task id). An agent asks the graph 'what can I work on that is NOT waiting on a human?' and gets a list. This is what lets the LOCAL tier keep working through the night on tasks whose details are already settled, while the questions queue up for Matt. Without it, one unanswered question stalls everything behind it." ;
               kpred:remaining    "kpred:blocks on question entries; scripts/agent/unblocked.ts to list actionable work; graph-lint check that no task is silently blocked forever." .

kb:async-digest rdf:type       ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 3 — the rolling digest" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:async-orchestration ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/agent/digest.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "scripts/agent/__tests__/async-loop.test.ts" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "PARTIAL, and the gap is the interesting part. Findings DO reach the graph — every one is dual-written to knowledge.pending.jsonl as a pending fact on the entity it concerns. But the primary artifact is a hand-appended markdown file (reckons-workspace/DIGEST.md), and the kb:digest ENTITY this phase specified — rendered through the WebPage/publish machinery, 'just a graph node like anything else' — was never built. So the digest is a second source of truth in a product whose thesis is that there should not be one." ;
               hnav:order   3 ;
               kpred:description  "One report that GROWS, instead of many that interrupt. Agents append findings to a digest entity in the graph (dated, typed: bug-found / claim-falsified / test-added / question-raised / decision-needed). Matt reads one accumulating page when he returns, in the app, with the graph context attached — not twenty chat messages he must reconstruct. Renders through the existing WebPage/publish machinery, so it is just a graph node like anything else." ;
               kpred:remaining    "kb:digest entity + append helper; render in-app; per-session sections." .

kb:async-visual-test rdf:type  ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 4 — visually test the ask/answer loop" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:async-orchestration ;
