               kpred:remaining    "tests/visual/user-stories/async-questions.test.ts + screenshots." .

kb:auto-merge rdf:type         ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Auto-merge of accumulated facts" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F80.1" ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/merge-band.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/pending-dedup.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/merge-band.test.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/pending-dedup.test.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/stores/workspace.svelte.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/lexical-similarity.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/lexical-similarity.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "The deterministic CORE is built and tested (16 tests, 2026-07-15). merge-band.ts is the one executable copy of the decided band (auto >=0.90 / suggest 0.50-0.90 / else none) governing merge, link AND predicate-sameness. pending-dedup.ts applies it: findPendingDuplicates() folds exact-identical pending facts (similarity 1.0 -> auto, highest-confidence kept, datatype/lang respected, deterministic); findMergeSuggestions() surfaces same-predicate semantic near-dupes in the suggest band without acting (similarity injected, so the core stays model-free). WIRED (type-checked) into drainAndImportPending (workspace.svelte.ts): the MCP pending drain now folds exact duplicate COMPLETE facts within a batch before review — partial facts (F32 questions) are deliberately left alone so their blocks/question metadata is never silently dropped. STILL SCAFFOLDED, not functional: the drain wiring is not yet OBSERVED running live (needs a connected workspace, not drivable headlessly); cross-batch dedupe against already-imported pending is not built (needs a graph read); the review UI does not yet show a fold count; and the semantic tier's similarity source (F22 embeddings) is not connected." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:async-orchestration ;
               kpred:description  "Facts pile up while the user is away, and many are the same fact said twice by different agents. Where two pending statements are confidently identical after entity normalization (F22) they should MERGE rather than both queue for review — the user should never triage the same finding twice. Merging is confidence-gated and always reviewable; an auto-merge is a suggestion the graph made, not a fact the graph invented." ;
               kpred:auto-merge-threshold "0.9" ;
               kpred:suggest-merge-floor  "0.5" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:predicate-manager ;
               kpred:decided      "One merge band, applied to BOTH entity merges AND predicate-sameness (is this predicate link the same as that one): auto-merge at >=0.90 similarity (after F22 normalization for entities); SUGGEST a merge (queued for review, never applied silently) in the 0.50-0.90 band; below 0.50 no action. The suggest band IS the answer to the silent-destruction risk — nothing merges unreviewed unless it is >=90% identical, and everything less confident becomes a reviewable suggestion, not a silent action. (Matt, 2026-07-15.) Status stays planned: this is the decided spec, not yet wired; kb:predicate-manager today does manual, exact-match merge only." .

# -- F81: Local task orchestration & scheduling (in Reckons.AI, not in a cloud cron) ---
# The cloud cron FAILED in exactly the way that matters: it fired perfectly on schedule
# (last_fired_at 2026-07-12T20:40:18Z) and produced NOTHING — no commits, no output, no
# error anyone saw. Worse, afterwards next_run_at still displayed a future time while
# enabled was false, so the UI said "armed" about a thing that would never run again.
# A scheduler you cannot observe is not a scheduler, it is a rumour.
#
# So orchestration comes home. Reckons.AI already holds the work (the graph), the
# questions (partial facts), and the findings (the digest). It should hold the SCHEDULE
# too — locally, observably, and with the run's outcome written back as facts.

# -- F90: Content generation — the first domain where "done" is not a test ------
#
# Coding orchestration is the EASY case, and it is worth saying so plainly before generalizing
# from it. Code is machine-verifiable: does it compile, do the tests pass, does align stay
# green. `done-when` is a command with an exit code, and the whole loop (F87/F89) leans on that.
#
# Content generation breaks it. "Render the hero asset" has no exit code. A Blender script that
# completes successfully and emits a black frame has "passed". The acceptance criterion is not
# a test — it is a LOOK, and a look is judgment.
#
# This is exactly the verifiability axis (F88) meeting a domain where the honest answer is not
# `code`. It is where the orchestration stops being about coding and starts being general — and
# where it would be easiest to quietly lie to ourselves that a green exit code means the asset
# is good.

kb:content-orchestration rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Content generation orchestration (Blender, headless, over MCP)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F90" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:agent-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:verifiability-axis ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:asset-viewer ;
               kpred:description  "Headless Blender (`blender --background --python`) exposed as an MCP tool, so an agent can generate, render and inspect 3D content the same way it queries the graph. The scene is DESCRIBED IN THE GRAPH — objects, materials, camera, lights as entities — and the Blender script is GENERATED from it. That means an asset has provenance: you can ask why a thing is the colour it is, diff two scenes, and regenerate one from a graph rather than from a .blend nobody can read." ;
               kpred:principle    "THE SCENE IS A GRAPH, NOT A SCRIPT. A generated .blend or .py is a derived artifact; the graph is the source. Otherwise the asset pipeline becomes exactly the thing this product exists to replace — a binary blob whose reasoning is lost." ;
               kpred:principle    "A GREEN EXIT CODE IS NOT A GOOD IMAGE. Blender will happily render a black frame and exit 0. Any `done-when` that only checks the process succeeded is a lie the loop will tell itself at scale." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:agent-orchestration ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:verifiability-axis ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:blender-mcp ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:visual-acceptance .

kb:blender-mcp rdf:type        ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 1 — headless Blender over MCP" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:content-orchestration ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/content/blender-render.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "scripts/content/__tests__/blender-render.test.ts" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "SCAFFOLDED, not functional. The render harness works — scene -> deterministic Python -> headless Cycles render, verified against real Blender 5.2. NOT yet an MCP tool and NOT yet driven from the graph (scene is a plain object, not a ktype:Scene subgraph). Those are the remaining work." ;
               hnav:order   1 ;
               kpred:description  "An MCP tool surface over `blender --background --python`: render a scene described in the graph, export GLB, inspect the result. Runs LOCALLY — Blender is free, offline and installed on the user's machine, which fits the thesis exactly: no operator, no API key, no upload of your work to someone else's renderer. The existing GLB asset viewer already consumes the output, and qwen2.5vl is already the visual gate." ;
               kpred:principle    "Local by default, and the reason is the thesis, not thrift. A cloud renderer means your unreleased work sits on someone else's disk — the same objection as hosted sync (kb:avoid-hosted-sync)." ;
               kpred:remaining    "mcp-server: blender_render (scene entity -> image/GLB), blender_inspect (what is actually IN this file). Scene vocabulary: ktype:Scene, kpred:has-object / material / camera / light. Generate the .py FROM the graph; never hand-maintain the script." .

kb:visual-acceptance rdf:type  ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 2 — done-when for things that have no exit code" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:content-orchestration ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/content/blender-render.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "The deterministic image check (checkImage) is built and tested: it DECODES the PNG pixels and catches the flat/black frame that Blender renders while exiting 0. Verified against a real black render (variation 0.000, rejected) and a real scene (39% of pixels vary, accepted). Its first version sampled COMPRESSED bytes and passed a black frame as a real image — the exact confidently-wrong-checker failure, fixed by decoding actual pixels and measuring against the DOMINANT colour, not the first pixel. VLM scoring and user-taste routing (the other two rungs) are not built." ;
               hnav:order   2 ;
               kpred:description  "The generalization the whole orchestration needs. A content task's acceptance criterion cannot be a test, so it is one of: a DETERMINISTIC check (the image is not uniformly one colour; the GLB parses; the file is not 0 bytes; the frame is not empty) — cheap, script tier, and it catches the black-frame class outright; a VLM JUDGMENT (qwen2.5vl scores the render against the brief and the design rubric) — agent tier, a PROPOSAL, never an auto-accept; or THE USER (verifiable-by `user` — taste is not delegable, and pretending otherwise is how you ship forty assets nobody likes)." ;
               kpred:principle    "Push as much as possible into the deterministic check FIRST. A black frame, an empty scene and a 0-byte export are RULES, and rules cost nothing to triage. Sending those to a VLM moves cost from generation to review rather than removing it (F74.3)." ;
               kpred:principle    "Taste routes to the user, and it must be ALLOWED to. The verifiability axis exists precisely so a domain like this can say `user` out loud instead of dressing a preference up as a passing check." ;
               kpred:remaining    "kpred:done-when accepting a non-command criterion; deterministic image checks (non-uniform, non-empty, parses); VLM scoring harness against kb:web-uiux-rubric; asset review in the queue, gated by F88." .

# -- F89: The loop — plan, assign, code, review, merge, repeat ------------------
#
# Matt's flow: wake Opus on a schedule -> review pending work -> assign -> sub-agents code
# -> review results (TTL and code) -> merge both (git for code, MCP merge for the graph).
#
# That flow is right. What follows is what it does not yet say, because the gaps are where
# a loop like this fails silently — and a loop that fails silently at 3am is worse than no
# loop, since you will trust it.

kb:autonomous-loop rdf:type    ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "The loop — plan, assign, code, review, merge, repeat" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F89" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:agent-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:co-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:work-tiering ;
               kpred:description  "A scheduled Opus orchestrator drains the task queue: it triages what is pending, assigns unblocked work to the cheapest competent harness, waits, then reviews what came back. Code merges through git behind the existing gates (align, tests, build-guard, script tier). Graph changes merge through Reckons.AI's own cross-graph merge, because a sub-agent's findings are a GRAPH, not a diff — and merging graphs is the thing this product is for. The user is never the bottleneck and never the rubber stamp: they are asked only what only they can answer." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:agent-orchestration ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:verifiability-axis ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:loop-idea-inbox ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:loop-subagent-graphs ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:loop-definition-of-done ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:loop-job-grouping ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:loop-safety .

kb:loop-idea-inbox rdf:type    ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 1 — ideas are a GRAPH, diffed against the roadmap" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:autonomous-loop ;
               hnav:order   1 ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:description  "Matt: 'ideas could be a separate graph and diff against roadmap'. That is the right shape, and it is better than an inbox — because it REUSES THE PRODUCT instead of inventing a sidecar. Ideas land in their own graph with no structure demanded at capture. Diffing that graph against the roadmap then answers, for free, the three questions that matter: what here is NEW, what REINFORCES something already planned, and what CONFLICTS with something we have already decided. That third one is the payoff, and an inbox could never give it: 'this idea contradicts a principle you hold' is precisely the thing you want said back to you, and precisely the thing a list of notes cannot say." ;
               kpred:principle    "CAPTURE MUST COST NOTHING OR IT WILL NOT HAPPEN. Friction at the moment of the idea — a required field, a type, a parent — trades the idea for the metadata, and the idea was the valuable half. The structure is recovered later, by DIFFING, not demanded up front." ;
               kpred:principle    "An idea graph is the mission in miniature: it is mostly well-formed absences. Subject and predicate known, object open. The orchestrator's job is to ask about the objects — not to invent them." ;
               kpred:reuses       "The machinery already exists and is shipped: multi-graph registry, importAsNewKb, computeDiff/semanticDiff (new · reinforces · conflicts · refines), cross-graph align (F16), and the MergeReview UI. An idea graph is just another graph, which is the whole point." ;
               kpred:remaining    "A low-friction capture surface (chat, CLI, voice) writing to an `ideas` graph; scheduled diff of ideas -> roadmap; conflicts surfaced as questions the orchestrator asks; accepted ideas promoted into the roadmap as planned features (a USER-AUTHORITY act, per F88 — minting a feature is authorship, not observation)." .

kb:loop-subagent-graphs rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 2 — sub-agents write their own graphs; Opus merges" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:autonomous-loop ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:has-file     "mcp-server/src/merge.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "mcp-server/src/__tests__/merge.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "kb_merge MCP tool, verified over the real JSON-RPC protocol. First call on roadmap -> production surfaced 23 real conflicts, including the roadmap claiming the MCP server has 10 tools while production says 20." ;
               hnav:order   2 ;
               kpred:description  "A sub-agent does not return a chat summary; it returns a GRAPH — its findings, its claims, and its open questions, in its own namespace. Opus then merges those graphs into the trunk. This is the sharpest possible dogfooding: merging independent graphs, with provenance and a review status per fact, is the product. The primitives already exist (multi-graph registry, importAsNewKb, cross-graph align F16, MergeReview UI); what is missing is an MCP tool so an ORCHESTRATOR can drive the merge, not just a human clicking." ;
               kpred:principle    "A sub-agent's output is a CLAIM, not a fact. It arrives as pending, in its own graph, and becomes trunk only by passing a competent gate. An agent that can write directly to the trunk is not a sub-agent, it is an unreviewed committer." ;
               kpred:remaining    "kb_merge MCP tool (align two graphs -> proposals); per-agent graph namespaces; conflict surfacing when two agents assert different objects for the same subject+predicate." .

kb:loop-definition-of-done rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 3 — a task must carry how it will be checked" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:autonomous-loop ;
               hnav:order   3 ;
               kpred:description  "'Review results' is unbounded unless the task said, before it started, what would count as done. Every task carries an acceptance criterion that a MACHINE can evaluate — a test that must pass, `npm run align` green, a named assertion — and its verifiable-by class decides who signs off: code/test go to the script tier and to Opus, never to Matt; a roadmap or principle change goes to Matt however checkable it is." ;
               kpred:principle    "A task without a machine-checkable definition of done is not a task, it is a wish. Its 'completion' will be an agent's opinion of its own work — an unverifiable claim, made by the party it benefits." ;
               kpred:remaining    "kpred:done-when on AgentTask; the orchestrator refuses to assign a task that has none." .

kb:loop-job-grouping rdf:type  ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 4 — group the queue so it can be judged in one pass" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:autonomous-loop ;
               hnav:order   4 ;
               kpred:description  "Review cost scales with the number of DECISIONS, not the number of facts. Forty facts from one agent about one entity, all of the same kind, are ONE decision presented forty times. Group the queue by (task, agent, subject, gate) and let a group be accepted, rejected, or opened in a single act — with the outliers in a group surfaced rather than hidden, because a batch accept is exactly where a bad fact slips through." ;
               kpred:principle    "Batching must make the ODD ONE OUT more visible, not less. A group that hides its dissenter has converted review into rubber-stamping." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Grouping in the review queue; batch accept/reject; outlier highlighting within a group." .

kb:loop-safety rdf:type        ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 5 — the ways this loop fails silently" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:autonomous-loop ;
               hnav:order   5 ;
               kpred:description  "A loop that fails silently at 3am is worse than no loop, because you will trust it. The known failure modes, each of which has already bitten this project once: (1) THE RUNNER DIED — a cron fired exactly on schedule, produced nothing, reported nothing, and still displayed a future run time. (2) THE HARNESS RAN OUT OF BUDGET — Opus hits a usage limit mid-orchestration and the task is 'in progress' forever; leases (F87 phase 3) hand it back. (3) DOUBLE ASSIGNMENT — two woken orchestrators take the same task; claims fix it. (4) THE TOOL WAS WRONG — published-graph-guard reported 166 phantom violations and kept a real gate switched off for a day. (5) THE AGENT REVIEWED NOTHING — a cold model load failed and the code review reported a clean run having read zero files." ;
               kpred:principle    "SILENCE MUST NEVER LOOK LIKE SUCCESS. Every run writes its outcome back, including 'I did nothing, and here is why'. A green log that is always green is not a record." ;
               kpred:principle    "A FINDING IS A CLAIM. A tool reporting a violation is a party with an interest in having found one. Verify the finding before acting on it — especially when acting on it means weakening a control." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Run outcomes as facts; lease expiry sweep; a rollback path for a merge that lands broken on main (production deploys from main)." .

# -- F88: Co-orchestration — Shelly and Claude Code, either side of the user -----
#
# Shelly does not need to become Claude Code. That would be a worse Claude Code, and it
# would abandon the one thing Shelly has that Claude Code does not: THE USER IS PRESENT.
#
# The two are co-orchestrators, and they are divided by their RELATIONSHIP TO TRUTH:
#
#   CLAUDE CODE works where the source of truth is IN THE REPOSITORY. "Does this file
#   exist", "does this test pass", "does this status match the code" — all checkable, all
#   verifiable, no human needed. It should never ask the user what it can verify itself.
#
#   SHELLY works where THERE IS NO SUCH SOURCE. A person's business, their research, their
#   organization — the truth is not in a file anyone can grep. It is in the user's head, or
#   in a document only they can vouch for, or it is genuinely unknown. Shelly cannot verify
#   it and must not pretend to. Its job is to ELICIT it, LABEL it honestly as attested, and
#   mark clearly what is still missing.
#
# This is the thesis applied to ourselves: an unverifiable claim, made by the party it
# benefits, is not evidence. A user-attested fact is not worthless — it is just not the
# same KIND of fact as a verified one, and the graph must never launder one into the other.

kb:co-orchestration rdf:type   ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Co-orchestration — Shelly and Claude Code either side of the user" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F88" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:shelly-chat ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:agent-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:partial-facts ;
               kpred:description  "Two agents, one graph, and a human between them. Claude Code holds the CODE, where truth is verifiable and no one need be asked. Shelly holds the CONVERSATION, where truth lives in the user and can only be attested. Neither is the orchestrator; the graph is, and all three drain it. Shelly is not being grown into a coding agent — it is being given the skills that only make sense with a person in the room." ;
               kpred:principle    "SHELLY IS NOT A SMALLER CLAUDE CODE. It is the agent that can ask. Making it write code would trade the one advantage it has — the user is present — for a capability that is already covered better elsewhere." ;
               kpred:principle    "AN AGENT MUST NOT ASK WHAT IT CAN VERIFY, AND MUST NOT ASSERT WHAT IT CANNOT. Asking the user something the repo already answers wastes the scarcest resource in the system. Asserting something only the user could know is a fabrication with good manners." ;
               kpred:principle    "Where there is no source of truth, say so. A well-formed absence — subject and predicate known, object '?' — is the most useful node in the graph, and it is the only honest thing to write when nobody knows the answer yet." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:partial-facts ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:verifiability-axis ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:shelly-skills .

kb:verifiability-axis rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 1 — record HOW a fact could be checked" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:co-orchestration ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/verifiability.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/verifiability.test.ts" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "SCAFFOLDED, not functional — and the distinction is the point. The axis exists and is tested (17 tests): Statement.verifiableBy, inferVerifiability(), competentGate(), requiresUserAuthority(), gateFor(). NOTHING CONSUMES IT YET. The review queue still puts every fact in front of the user regardless of who is competent to judge it. Calling this `functional` would be exactly the overclaim kb:honest-status forbids." ;
               kpred:principle    "VERIFIABLE IS NOT APPROVABLE. A script can verify that a principle IS WRITTEN; it cannot approve that it is the RIGHT principle. The roadmap and the tenets are DECISIONS — the user is their author, not their auditor — so authority OVERRIDES verifiability, however checkable the fact happens to be. Conversely `kpred:has-status \"functional\"` is a claim ABOUT THE CODE, and putting it to the user invites them to rubber-stamp their own wishes; a machine should check that one." ;
               kpred:principle    "UNCLASSIFIED FAILS TOWARD THE HUMAN. A fact whose verifiability nobody has established is never machine-approved. An unclassified fact silently auto-accepted at machine speed is the precise quiet failure this axis exists to prevent." ;
               hnav:order   1 ;
               kpred:description  "Every fact gains kpred:verifiable-by, naming what would settle it: `code` (a file, a symbol — a script can check it), `test` (a suite asserts it), `source` (a cited passage in an ingested document), `user` (attested by the person; nothing else backs it), or `unknown` (nobody has established this, and pretending otherwise is the failure). This is what lets an agent ROUTE: a `code` fact belongs to Claude Code and the script tier and should never be put to a human; a `user` fact belongs to Shelly and must never be quietly invented." ;
               kpred:principle    "Provenance answers WHERE a fact came from. Verifiability answers WHETHER ANYONE COULD CHECK IT. They are different questions, and the second is the one that decides who should be handling the fact." ;
               kpred:example      "In the Reckons.AI repo almost every fact is `code` or `test` — which is exactly why this project can be aggressively automated, and why a user's business graph cannot. The tooling must not assume its own conditions generalize." ;
               kpred:remaining    "kpred:verifiable-by on the statement model; render it in the review queue; graph-lint check that a `code`-verifiable fact actually names a file that exists." .

kb:shelly-skills rdf:type      ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 2 — the skills that need a person in the room" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:co-orchestration ;
               hnav:order   2 ;
               kpred:description  "Shelly's action vocabulary grows along ONE axis: things that require the user. ASK — when Shelly does not know, it emits a partial fact (object '?', plus what it blocks) rather than guessing; a guess silently entered into a knowledge graph is worse than a stalled task. ANSWER — Shelly walks the user through the pending queue conversationally, so the review backlog can be cleared by talking instead of clicking. ATTEST — a fact the user supplies is written with verifiable-by `user`, never laundered into looking verified. It does NOT gain: a shell, a file editor, or a code writer." ;
               kpred:learned-from "Shelly is already the HUMAN ADAPTER of F87 and nobody had noticed. F87 phase 2 lists adapters for Claude Code, for a local Ollama script, and for 'the human (a partial fact in the review queue, which is already an adapter and was not recognized as one)'. Shelly is the conversational face of that adapter." ;
               kpred:remaining    "KBAction: ask_question (emit partial fact) + answer_question (resolve one from the queue). adjust_view already fixed to expose timeline + hierarchy — the view-control API could not previously express two layouts the graph renders." .

# -- F87: Agent orchestration — the graph IS the orchestration config ------------
#
# F81 answered WHERE work executes (the runner: Worker, desktop process, MCP server).
# It never named the other axis: WHAT AGENT DOES THE REASONING. Claude Code, Codex,
# Qwen Code, a local Ollama script, a human in the Review tab — these are HARNESSES,
# and they are not interchangeable with runners. Conflating them is why "bring your
# own harness" was not expressible.
#
# Two axes, one queue:
#   RUNNER  — where the process lives      (F81: Worker / desktop / MCP)
#   HARNESS — who does the thinking        (F87: Claude Code / Codex / Ollama / human)
#
# pilotfish's real lesson is not its model routing, it is that its orchestration is
# CONFIG, not runtime code — three files, no daemon. Reckons.AI already has the config
# format, and it is the graph. So the graph does not need an orchestrator bolted on;
# the graph IS the orchestrator, and a harness is a thing that drains it.

kb:agent-orchestration rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Agent orchestration — bring your own harness" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F87" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:local-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:work-tiering ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:async-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:competitive-landscape ;
               kpred:description  "A TASK IS A TRIPLE. Schedules, dependencies, tiers, prompts and outcomes live in the graph, and any harness can drain the queue: Claude Code, Codex, Qwen Code, a local Ollama script, or a human answering in the Review tab. The graph is the orchestration CONFIG — portable, diffable, reviewable, and outliving whichever agent CLI is fashionable this quarter. Reckons.AI does not become an agent; it becomes the thing agents agree on." ;
               kpred:principle    "PORTABILITY IS THE PRODUCT. Claude Code is a harness, not a platform. An orchestration layer welded to one vendor's CLI dies with that CLI — and a knowledge graph whose task queue only one agent can read is a knowledge graph with a vendor lock in the middle of it." ;
               kpred:principle    "The graph is the config. pilotfish orchestrates with three config files and NO runtime code; the reason that works is that the config is the whole design. We already have a config format with provenance, review status, diffing and a UI — it is the graph. Adding a second, private, YAML-shaped orchestration format would be a defeat." ;
               kpred:principle    "A harness must be REPLACEABLE MID-TASK. If Claude Code hits a usage limit, the task returns to the queue and Codex — or the local model, or the human — can take it. This is only possible because the task's state is in the GRAPH, not in the agent's context window. An agent's context is not a database." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:local-orchestration ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:partial-facts ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:orch-task-vocab ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:orch-harness-adapter ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:orch-claim-lease ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:orch-jobs-to-ttl .

kb:orch-task-vocab rdf:type    ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 1 — the task vocabulary (a task is a triple)" ;
               kpred:schedules    "Scheduling lives in the GRAPH, as kpred:every — an INTERVAL, not a cron expression. Cron says 'at 03:40 on Tuesdays', which assumes a machine that is awake with a daemon that fires; we know what that promise is worth, because the cloud cron fired exactly on schedule, produced nothing, reported nothing, and went on showing a future run time. An interval claims only 'not more often than this', and whichever runner wakes next drains what is due. The next due time is computed from when the run ACTUALLY happened, so a machine asleep for a week wakes owing one run, not seven. DRAIN, DO NOT SCHEDULE." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:agent-orchestration ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/agent-task.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/agent-task.test.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/agent/runner.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "The loop closes, demonstrated end to end on reckons-workspace/tasks.ttl. Run 1: three tasks claimed, executed, INDEPENDENTLY verified, outcomes written back. A task with no done-when was REFUSED; a task with an unmet dependency was HELD. Run 2: the finished tasks were skipped and the blocked task UNBLOCKED ITSELF and ran, because its dependency had completed. Run 3: idle. An expired lease with no outcome is detected and requeued." ;
               hnav:order   1 ;
               kpred:description  "ktype:AgentTask with a defined vocabulary, so a schedule is a fact and not a config file: kpred:goal (what to do, in words a harness can act on), kpred:tier (script | local-agent | frontier — routes to the cheapest harness that can do it), kpred:harness (a PREFERENCE, not a requirement — 'any' is valid and is the default), kpred:due-at / kpred:every (drain-not-schedule, per F81), kpred:blocked-by (a partial fact, a question, or another task), kpred:writes-to (where the outcome lands: pending.jsonl, a branch, a PR), kpred:outcome (written back on completion, INCLUDING 'did nothing, and here is why')." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Define the predicates in the graph; graph-lint checks (no task blocked forever, no task without a tier, no due-at in an unparseable format); render tasks in-app." .

kb:orch-harness-adapter rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 2 — harness adapters (bring your own)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:agent-orchestration ;
               hnav:order   2 ;
               kpred:description  "A thin adapter per harness: take a task, hand it to that agent in its native shape, capture the outcome as facts. The interface is deliberately tiny — canRun(task), run(task) -> outcome — because the harness is a PLUGIN, not a dependency. Adapters ship for Claude Code (a prompt + the graph context via kb_compress), a local Ollama script (the existing offline/ harness), and the human (a partial fact in the Review tab, which is already an adapter and was not recognized as one)." ;
               kpred:learned-from "unsnooze (MIT) proves the shape at scale: ONE ledger, ONE daemon, and a per-CLI adapter for seven different agents (Claude Code, Codex, Grok, Qwen, Kimi, OpenCode, Antigravity). Detection and revival differ per CLI; the ledger does not. That is exactly the seam we need, and it is evidence the seam holds in practice rather than only in a design document." ;
               kpred:remaining    "adapters/claude-code.ts, adapters/ollama.ts, adapters/human.ts; a registry keyed by kpred:harness; a runner that picks the cheapest adapter whose canRun() accepts the task." .

kb:orch-claim-lease rdf:type   ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 3 — claims, leases, and surviving a usage limit" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:agent-orchestration ;
               hnav:order   3 ;
               kpred:description  "The moment more than one runner drains one queue, two of them will take the same task. A task therefore carries kpred:claimed-by + kpred:claim-expires (a LEASE, not a lock — a runner that dies must not hold a task forever). When a harness stops on a usage limit, the lease lapses and the task returns to the queue for a different harness. This is the concrete mechanism behind 'a harness must be replaceable mid-task'." ;
               kpred:learned-from "unsnooze exists ENTIRELY because agent sessions die on usage limits and nothing notices. Our queue currently has no concept of a harness running out of budget — a task handed to Claude Code at a limit boundary would simply stop, and the graph would say it was in progress forever. That is the same silent-failure class as the cron that fired and produced nothing." ;
               kpred:remaining    "kpred:claimed-by / kpred:claim-expires; lease expiry sweep; graph-lint check for tasks claimed by a runner that has not reported in." .

kb:orch-jobs-to-ttl rdf:type   ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label   "Phase 4 — jobs.json becomes a graph" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:agent-orchestration ;
               hnav:order   4 ;
               kpred:description  "scripts/offline/jobs.json is ALREADY a task queue with tiers, enablement and a blocking flag — it is just written in the one format the product does not use. Migrating it to TTL makes the offline jobs first-class graph citizens: queryable, reviewable in-app, diffable, and schedulable by the same runner as everything else. It also dogfoods the vocabulary on a queue that already works, before betting anything new on it." ;
               kpred:honest-note  "This is the tell that the design is right, and it is slightly embarrassing: we built a task registry with tiers and dependencies and put it in JSON, inside a product whose entire thesis is that this belongs in a graph." ;
               kpred:remaining    "static/reckons-jobs.ttl; run-all.ts reads the graph; keep jobs.json working until the TTL path is proven." .

kb:local-orchestration rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Local task orchestration & scheduling" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F81" ;
               kpred:has-status   "in-progress" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/agent/schedule.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "scripts/agent/runner.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/agent-task.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/agent-task.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "Schedules live in the GRAPH (reckons-workspace/schedules.ttl, ktype:Schedule). `npm run schedule` reads the TTL, reports what is due, runs the due ones, and writes last-run/next-due back — verified end to end: a schedule executed `orchestrate --json` and its state was tracked. kpred:every is an INTERVAL, not cron: the next due time is computed from when it actually ran, so a machine asleep for a week wakes owing one run, not seven. Whatever triggers it (cron, systemd, unsnooze, a human) reads the graph to know what to do — the plan is not baked into a crontab nobody can diff. MODEL BATCHING (2026-07-15): a task declares kpred:model, and orderForModelBatching runs same-model local-agent tasks CONSECUTIVELY — Ollama + RAM cannot switch models cheaply, so keeping one model warm across its whole batch avoids a reload between every task. Script tier stays first (free, no model); the sort is stable so priority within a model is preserved. 5 tests; the runner logs each model-batch boundary because every boundary is a real reload." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:async-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:work-tiering ;
               kpred:description  "Tasks, schedules and outcomes live in the graph and run locally. A task is an entity (what to do, which TIER it belongs to, what it depends on, what question blocks it); a schedule is a triple; a run writes its result back as facts. That makes the whole loop QUERYABLE: what ran, what it found, what it is waiting on, what it never got to. Local Ollama/WASM agents drain the unblocked queue continuously; Claude Code takes what needs frontier reasoning; the human answers questions whenever they like. Nothing waits on anything it does not have to." ;
               kpred:principle    "A scheduler you cannot observe is not a scheduler, it is a rumour. Every run writes its outcome back to the graph — including 'I did nothing, and here is why'." ;
               kpred:principle    "Silence must never look like success. The cloud cron fired, produced nothing, and reported nothing; that is the failure mode to design against." ;
               kpred:correction   "PRECISION, 2026-07-13: the cron did NOT fail. It fired on time (last_fired_at 20:40:18Z, exactly as scheduled). What failed was the RUNNER (the cloud agent produced no commits) and the OBSERVABILITY (nothing reported that). Blaming the scheduling primitive would lead to fixing the wrong component. The lesson is about runners and reporting, not about cron." ;
               kpred:principle    "THE QUEUE IS THE CONTRACT; THE RUNNER IS PLUGGABLE. Do not choose between cron and the browser — they optimize different axes. cron gives RELIABLE TIMING on a NARROW set of machines (Unix-only; Windows needs Task Scheduler; it does not exist on phone or tablet; the machine must be awake). A Web Worker gives BROAD REACH with OPPORTUNISTIC timing (every device, one codebase, but only while the app is open). Put the task queue in the GRAPH, and let any runner drain it: the in-app Worker by default (all devices), an optional desktop process for wake-when-closed (driven by cron/launchd/Task Scheduler), the MCP server when an agent is already talking to it. Each runner claims tasks and writes outcomes back. No runner is load-bearing, so none of them failing silently can stop the system — and the queue tells you which ones are actually doing anything." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Task entities + kpred:runs-at / kpred:blocked-by; a local runner draining the unblocked queue; run outcomes written back as facts; surface the queue in-app." ;
               kpred:decided      "WEB WORKER IN THE APP (Matt, 2026-07-13), for cross-device reach. The browser is the most portable runtime there is, and it is already open all day — so the local tier lives where the user already is: desktop, laptop, tablet, phone, same code. WASM models (transformers.js) run inside a Worker, so the whole local tier ships with the app and needs nothing installed." ;
               kpred:constraint   "HONEST LIMIT — A WORKER CANNOT BE A SCHEDULER. A Web Worker lives only while a tab is open. A Service Worker survives page close but browsers kill idle ones in ~30s, and true timed wakeup (Periodic Background Sync) is Chromium-only, needs an INSTALLED PWA, and is gated behind engagement heuristics — Safari and Firefox do not implement it. So 'fire at 3:40 with nothing open' is not something the browser will honestly deliver on every device, and designing as if it will is how you get another silent failure." ;
               kpred:principle    "DO NOT SCHEDULE — DRAIN. Invert the model: a task carries a due-time, and whenever the app is open the Worker drains everything unblocked and due. 'Run at T' becomes 'the next time you are here, this is ready'. That is strictly MORE reliable than the cron that fired and silently did nothing, because the queue and its outcomes are visible in the app: the user can SEE what ran, what is waiting, and what it is waiting on." ;
               kpred:principle    "Tiers by reach, not by preference. WASM-in-Worker is the only tier that runs on EVERY device, so it is the default local tier. Ollama is desktop-only (it needs localhost) and is an upgrade, not a requirement. Claude Code is the frontier tier. A task declares the weakest tier that can do it correctly, and the strongest available one takes it." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Task entities + kpred:due-at / kpred:blocked-by / kpred:min-tier; a Web Worker queue drainer (WASM tier); run outcomes written back as facts; the queue surfaced in-app so it is observable." ;
               kpred:decided      "INSTALLABLE PWA (Matt, 2026-07-13). Already configured (@vite-pwa/sveltekit, vite.config.ts) — installable, offline-capable, on the home screen. Worth it on its own merits regardless of scheduling." ;
               kpred:constraint   "AN INSTALLED PWA IS STILL NOT A SCHEDULER. Periodic Background Sync unlocks on Chromium once installed, but the BROWSER decides whether and how often it fires, from engagement heuristics — commonly no more than once every ~12h, and never at a time you choose. Safari and Firefox do not implement it. So treat it as an OPPORTUNISTIC BONUS on top of drain-when-open, never a foundation. Building on it would reproduce exactly the failure we just had: a scheduler that looks armed and quietly does nothing." ;
               kpred:open-question "For users who genuinely need wake-when-CLOSED at a chosen time: that is an OS capability, not a browser one. An optional desktop companion (or the existing MCP server) could do it. But for a local-first tool, 'work happens when the app is open' may simply be the honest bargain — and the app is open all day anyway." .

# -- F82: Browser fact-finding sessions (extension) ------------------------------
# The extension already has a Session tab. The missing half is the GRAPH: while you read,
# Reckons.AI should be quietly asking "do I already know about this?" — querying the graph
# with the page's key terms and content, and offering the links it genuinely finds.

kb:browser-fact-finding rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Browser fact-finding sessions (highlight, analyze, link)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F82" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:browser-extension ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:entity-normalization ;
               kpred:description  "Research in the browser, grounded in what you already know. (1) HIGHLIGHT: key statements on the page are marked as candidate facts — a passage, not a vibe, so every proposed triple keeps its excerpt and is verifiable against the page (kb:passage-grounding). (2) DEEP ANALYSIS ON DEMAND: the user asks, and only then does the expensive pass run — never a background crawl of everything they read. (3) LINK TO WHAT WE KNOW: query the graph with the page's key terms AND its content, surface the entities that genuinely overlap, and offer to connect the new facts to them." ;
               kpred:principle    "Disconnected data is less valuable — but a FORCED link is worse than an orphan. If the content genuinely does not overlap the graph, relate it to nothing and say so. An invented edge is a lie the graph tells itself, and it is the same failure as the fabricated citation in kb:passage-grounding: it looks like knowledge and it is not." ;
               kpred:principle    "Deep analysis is opt-in. Reading is not consent to be indexed; the user asks, or it does not happen." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Highlight → candidate triples with excerpts; on-demand deep analysis; graph query by key terms + page content; a link-confidence threshold below which we propose NO relation rather than a weak one." ;
               kpred:decided      "Similarity floor RESOLVED (Matt, 2026-07-15): the shared merge band — link at >=0.90, suggest 0.50-0.90, below 0.50 nothing (kb:link-confidence, kb:auto-merge). Semantic, and the predicate carries the signal." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:browser-extension .

# -- Predicate economy: the edge TYPE is the signal ------------------------------
# Matt, 2026-07-13, answering kpred:link-similarity-floor. Two claims, and the second
# is the one that actually matters:
#
#   1. The bar is SEMANTIC, not lexical — a synonym is a likely connection, so embeddings,
#      not string equality. (The NUMBER moved 2026-07-15: ~0.80 -> the shared 0.90 merge
#      band, so merge, link, and predicate-sameness all use one rule. See kb:link-confidence.)
#   2. THE PREDICATE IS THE MAIN CLUE TO A VALID LINK. Not the entity labels.
#
# Two nodes whose labels are synonyms is weak evidence. Two nodes joined by a MEANINGFUL
# predicate is strong evidence. And "is related to" is BS: it is a non-link wearing the
# costume of a link. It adds an edge, adds no knowledge, and makes the graph look
# connected while telling you nothing about HOW.
#
# The flip side is just as real. Graph value leans on the number of connection TYPES more
# than the number of connections: a vocabulary that is reused generalizes, and one that
# sprawls does not. Every predicate used exactly once is a private word — it cannot be
# queried across, cannot be reasoned over, and cannot be learned from.
#
# WE ARE GUILTY OF BOTH (measured 2026-07-13 across static/*.ttl): 351 edges (5.8%) are
# `related`/`relates-to` — and we say that same nothing in TWO vocabularies (skos:related
# 219, kpred:relates-to 128). Meanwhile 49 of 237 predicate types (21%) are used exactly
# once. Generic mush at one end, private sprawl at the other.

kb:link-confidence rdf:type    ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "Link confidence threshold" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:browser-fact-finding ;
               kpred:decided      "MOVED to the shared merge band (Matt, 2026-07-15), SUPERSEDING the ~0.80 of 2026-07-13: link at >=0.90, SUGGEST a link (reviewable) in 0.50-0.90, below 0.50 propose nothing — the same auto/suggest band as entity merge and predicate-sameness (kb:auto-merge). Still SEMANTIC, not lexical (embeddings, kb:embedding-model, a synonym is a likely connection), and the PREDICATE is still the main clue to a valid link, not the entity labels — only the numeric floor changed, to one rule across merge, link, and predicate-sameness." ;
               kpred:principle    "Below the bar, propose NOTHING. A forced link is worse than an orphan: disconnected data is merely less valuable, whereas an invented edge is a lie the graph tells itself — the same failure as a fabricated citation (kb:passage-grounding). It looks like knowledge and it is not." ;
               kpred:principle    "Confidence in the ENTITY match is necessary but not sufficient. The link must also name a real relation (kb:predicate-economy). Two entities being 90% the same thing does not tell you HOW they connect." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:predicate-economy ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:auto-merge .

# -- F83: Graph legibility — a 1888-triple graph is not a 1234-node graph -------
# Matt opened the roadmap graph and found it unusable: 1,888 triples, and on many devices
# it would not render at all. The diagnosis is not performance. It is a MODELLING MISTAKE
# IN THE VIEW: every object became a node, INCLUDING LITERALS — so a 265-character
# kpred:description was drawn as a node on the canvas.
#
# Measured on reckons-roadmap.ttl: 990 distinct literal values, of which 953 (96%) appear
# EXACTLY ONCE. Each is a leaf that can never link anything to anything. Meanwhile only 383
# triples (20%) are entity->entity — the actual graph.
#
# THE RULE: A LITERAL EARNS A NODE BY BEING SHARED.
#   "production" appears 53 times -> a category. Every production feature hangs off it.
#   a description appears once    -> it connects nothing. It is an ATTRIBUTE of its subject.
#
# This is kb:predicate-economy applied to VALUES instead of edges: a graph's power comes
# from what is SHARED. A unique value generalizes nothing, and an edge to it teaches nobody.
#
# RESULT on the real roadmap: 1,234 nodes -> 271 (78% fewer). 985 walls of text moved off
# the canvas and into the node panel, where they can actually be read. The graph did not get
# smaller — it stopped lying about what was in it.

kb:graph-legibility rdf:type   ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Graph legibility (attributes vs structure, filters, focus)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F83" ;
               kpred:has-status   "in-progress" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/graph-view.test.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/entity-review.test.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/graph-view.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/entity-review.ts" ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:predicate-economy ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:review-attention ;
               kpred:description  "Make a large graph readable rather than merely rendered. (1) LITERALS ARE ATTRIBUTES, NOT NODES, unless shared: a value used once connects nothing and belongs in the node panel; a value used 53 times is a category worth seeing. (2) FILTER BY PREDICATE — 'just show me the dependency graph' — with facets sorted by count so structural relations surface first. (3) FILTER BY TIME, so a graph can be read as it grew. (4) PROGRESSIVE DISCLOSURE via top-by-degree, keeping only edges whose BOTH endpoints survive, so the canvas never shows an edge vanishing into nothing." ;
               kpred:principle    "A literal earns a node by being SHARED. Appearing once means it connects nothing." ;
               kpred:principle    "A graph is a picture of RELATIONSHIPS. A value that relates nothing to nothing is not part of that picture, however important it is to read." ;
               kpred:principle    "The human has a context window too. kb_compress already refuses to hand an LLM the whole graph and hands it the relevant part instead; 1,234 nodes overruns a person exactly as surely as 116k tokens overruns a model. Show the part that matters." ;
               kpred:measured     "reckons-roadmap.ttl: 1888 triples, 1234 nodes -> 271 (78% fewer). 985 attributes moved to the node panel. 27 shared literals earned category nodes (production, planned, functional, high...). 903 edges drawn instead of 1888." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Predicate + time filters in the UI (the pure functions exist and are tested); focus/expand interaction. The entity-granularity review cards are now RENDERED in /review and verified in a browser (via F53's buildReviewPlan wiring; tests/e2e/review.test.ts, 2026-07-15) — groupPendingByEntity() condenses the flat row list into per-entity cards carrying their strongest F88 gate, with a by-entity/flat toggle. Still to do here: the graph-view predicate/time filters still need their UI on the canvas side." ;
               kpred:done         "Graph package & sync moved OUT of the canvas filter panel and INTO the Graphs tab (2026-07-13). It had been buried behind a disclosure, collapsed 'so the panel stays short' — which was the tell that it did not belong there. A filter panel should filter. Graph management has its own top-level tab precisely because it matters." .

# == THE TTL / TRIG SPLIT — two products, not two file formats ==================
# Matt, 2026-07-13, and it reframes everything above.
#
# PROVENANCE IS NOT A DATA STRUCTURE. IT IS AN ACCOUNTABILITY RELATION.
#
# A user writing g = urn:kbase:source/my-note is not asserting provenance. He is
# SELF-ATTESTING, and he can edit it whenever he likes. It carries no epistemic weight
# because there is nobody who can be held to it. "The user is a failure and a fool at
# times" is not an insult — it is a THREAT MODEL. A graph whose only authority is its own
# owner cannot be evidence of anything to anyone else.
#
# Note that this is the SAME PRINCIPLE Matt has now landed on three times, in three
# different costumes:
#   F66.1  a stated purpose is an attestation, not evidence — so the gate asks nothing.
#   F82    an invented edge is a lie the graph tells itself — so we link nothing weakly.
#   HERE   a self-asserted source is not a source — so a private graph has no provenance.
# In every case: AN UNVERIFIABLE CLAIM, MADE BY THE PARTY IT BENEFITS, IS NOT EVIDENCE.
#
# So the split is not a file-format choice. It is two products.

kb:ttl-trig-split rdf:type     ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "The TTL / TriG split — private power vs published accountability" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:reckons-ai ;
               kpred:principle    "PROVENANCE IS AN ACCOUNTABILITY RELATION, NOT A FIELD. It requires a party who can be held to it. A source the user controls and can rewrite is an attestation, not evidence." ;
               kpred:principle    "A PRIVATE GRAPH HAS NO PROVENANCE, AND DOES NOT NEED ANY. It is the user's own reasoning, on the user's own device. He is the authority, and that is fine — because he is the only audience. Provenance is a claim made TO SOMEONE ELSE." ;
               kpred:principle    "PUBLISHING IS THE MOMENT A GRAPH ACQUIRES AN OWNER, AND THEREFORE ACQUIRES PROVENANCE. Not manual file-sharing — handing someone a .ttl transfers no accountability. Official publication attributes the graph to a person or org who can be held to it." ;
               kpred:description  "TTL is the PRIVATE side: offline-capable, plain-text, fully under the user's control, no accountability and none required. TriG is the PUBLISHED side: named graphs carry an attributed, accountable publication context, which is what makes provenance mean anything. The two are not competing serializations — they are the individual product and the institutional one." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:data-egress-model ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:adult-content-policy .

kb:ttl-private-side rdf:type   ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "TTL — the private side (full power to the user)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:ttl-trig-split ;
               kpred:description  "Offline, local-first, plain text, editable by hand, exportable always (export is a RIGHT — kb:data-egress-model). The user is the sole authority over his own graph and needs no permission from anyone. There is no meaningful provenance here and none is claimed: g is a bookkeeping convenience, not evidence. This is the freedom half of the product, and it must stay uncompromised — the moment we require an account to reason privately, the thesis is dead." ;
               kpred:decided      "EXPORT / MOVE to another machine is plain TTL and requires NO owner/publisher — it is the user's own graph being relocated, making no claim on anybody, so it needs no provenance and no attribution. Only PUBLISHING (kb:trig-published-side) requires that. This keeps the private product frictionless: you can always pick up your graph and carry it elsewhere. (Matt, 2026-07-15.)" ;
               kpred:principle    "Full power to the user, and no pretence of authority. A private graph makes no claim on anybody." .

kb:trig-published-side rdf:type ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "TriG — the published side (accountable provenance)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:ttl-trig-split ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:enterprise-3ps ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:publish-safety-gate ;
               kpred:description  "A named graph is a PUBLICATION: a set of facts attributed to an accountable publisher, at a time, under a policy. That attribution is what converts a self-asserted source into real provenance — because a publisher can be checked, cited, disputed, and held responsible, and a private file cannot. This is where TriG earns its keep, and it is a DIFFERENT PRODUCT from the private side: enterprise, institutional, governed." ;
               kpred:principle    "The named graph is not 'my note'. It is 'published by X, at time T, under policy P'. That sentence is the provenance; the quad is merely how we store it." ;
               kpred:decided      "PUBLISHING emits TriG and REQUIRES owner/publisher information — a publication with no attributed publisher is a contradiction, so publishing is REFUSED until owner/publisher is set (this gates kb:publish-safety-gate). Refines the F75 'Turtle out' heuristic: the trigger for TriG is PUBLISHING, not source-count — a published graph is TriG even from a single source, because the named graph now carries the PUBLISHER, not merely the source. Private export stays TTL (kb:ttl-private-side). (Matt, 2026-07-15.) Decided spec, not yet wired: publisher identity + the publish-time gate are unbuilt (see remaining)." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Publisher identity as a first-class entity; publication as an event (who, when, under what policy); the publish-time gate that refuses to publish without owner/publisher; RBAC + People/Policy/Procedure overlay (kb:enterprise-3ps); a distinct market position and marketing angle from the private side." .

kb:trig-enterprise-overlay rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "TriG enterprise overlay (provenance + RBAC + 3Ps)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F84" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:trig-published-side ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:enterprise-3ps ;
               kpred:description  "The institutional half of Reckons.AI, built on TriG's named graphs. A quad's 4th element becomes the join point for everything the enterprise cares about: WHO published it (identity), WHO may read it (RBAC), UNDER WHAT policy and procedure it was produced (the 3 Ps), and WHEN. Detailed provenance stops being metadata and becomes the access-control surface itself — you do not grant access to triples, you grant access to PUBLICATIONS. Entirely separate positioning from the private, offline, user-owned TTL side; likely a separate marketing angle and possibly a separate name." ;
               kpred:open-question "Does the enterprise side share a codebase with the private side, or diverge? The data model is the same (quads); the trust model is the opposite (nobody is the authority over their own facts). That tension is worth resolving deliberately rather than discovering later." .

# == THE THESIS — what Reckons.AI actually believes ==============================
# Surfaced on the landing page, GENERATED from these triples (scripts/landing-principles.ts)
# so the marketing cannot drift from what the product actually does. Each tenet carries
# kpred:tenet-status so the page can be honest about what is BUILT versus what is BELIEVED:
# a principle we have not implemented is a commitment, and must not be dressed as a feature
# (kb:honest-status).
#
# The spine of it, arrived at three separate times from three different directions:
#   an unverifiable claim, made by the party it benefits, is not evidence.

kb:thesis rdf:type             ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "The thesis" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:reckons-ai ;
               kpred:description  "Most knowledge tools store what you know. Reckons.AI stores HOW YOU KNOW IT — and refuses to fake it when it cannot." .

kb:tenet-evidence rdf:type     ktype:Tenet ;
               rdfs:label   "An unverifiable claim, made by the party it benefits, is not evidence." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:thesis ;
               kpred:show-on-landing "true" ;
               kpred:tenet-status "belief" ;
               hnav:order   1 ;
               kpred:tenet-body   "This is the spine. We arrived at it three separate times from three different directions: a stated purpose does not unlock a content gate, a weak similarity does not justify a link, and a source you control yourself is not a source. Each time the answer was the same — so we stopped treating it as a rule and started treating it as the thesis." .

kb:tenet-citation rdf:type     ktype:Tenet ;
               rdfs:label   "We would rather show you no citation than a forged one." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:thesis ;
               kpred:show-on-landing "true" ;
               kpred:tenet-status "built" ;
               hnav:order   2 ;
               kpred:tenet-body   "Every extracted fact quotes the sentence it came from — and we CHECK that the quote is really in your source. Language models paraphrase, and a paraphrased citation is a forgery that looks right. If we cannot find the quote, we drop it and lower our confidence. A missing receipt is honest. A convincing fake is not." .

kb:tenet-link rdf:type         ktype:Tenet ;
               rdfs:label   "A forced link is worse than an orphan." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:thesis ;
               kpred:show-on-landing "true" ;
               kpred:tenet-status "belief" ;
               hnav:order   4 ;
               kpred:tenet-body   "Disconnected facts are merely less useful. An invented edge is a lie the graph tells itself — it LOOKS like knowledge and is not. So if a new fact does not genuinely connect to what you already know, we connect it to nothing and say so. 'Is related to' is a non-link wearing the costume of a link." .

kb:tenet-export rdf:type       ktype:Tenet ;
               rdfs:label   "Export is a right. Distribution is a privilege." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:thesis ;
               kpred:show-on-landing "true" ;
               kpred:tenet-status "built" ;
               hnav:order   5 ;
               kpred:tenet-body   "Your graph is a plain text file on your machine, and we will never withhold it from you — whatever it contains. But when WE are the one carrying your content to someone else, we are a participant in that delivery, and we take responsibility for what we carry. We gate only what we carry." .

kb:tenet-private rdf:type      ktype:Tenet ;
               rdfs:label   "A private graph makes no claim on anybody." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:thesis ;
               kpred:show-on-landing "true" ;
               kpred:tenet-status "built" ;
               hnav:order   6 ;
               kpred:tenet-body   "Think privately. Be wrong privately. Change your mind privately. Your own graph needs no permission, no account, and no provenance — because it makes no claim on anyone else. Provenance is a claim made TO SOMEONE; alone with your notes, there is nobody to substantiate it to, and no reason to pretend otherwise." .

kb:tenet-honesty rdf:type      ktype:Tenet ;
               rdfs:label   "We will not describe a control we do not have." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:thesis ;
               kpred:show-on-landing "true" ;
               kpred:tenet-status "built" ;
               hnav:order   7 ;
               kpred:tenet-body   "Our safety documentation states plainly which protections exist and which do not, and an automated check verifies them against the live code every week — recording the failures too. We have already caught ourselves overclaiming, and corrected it in public. A safety promise you cannot verify is just marketing." .

# -- F85: Context-aware view suggestions ----------------------------------------
# Shelly and the notification stack should offer the RIGHT filter or force for what the
# user is actually looking at — "47 of the facts on screen carry dates spanning 8 months;
# want a timeline?" — and say NOTHING otherwise.
#
# A SUGGESTION MUST BE EARNED BY THE DATA. An unearned suggestion is not merely useless, it
# is corrosive: it trains the user to ignore the suggester, and then the ONE good
# suggestion — the one that would have saved them ten minutes in a 1,200-node hairball —
# goes unread with all the rest. A nag that fires on a timer is a forced link wearing a
# different costume: it looks like help and it is not.

kb:view-suggestions rdf:type   ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Context-aware view suggestions" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F85" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/view-suggestions.test.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/view-suggestions.ts" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-legibility ;
               kpred:description  "Reads the REAL view context — the facts currently drawn, the entity types the user selected, the node count, the connectivity shape, the layout in use — and offers at most ONE warranted change. Rules fire only on evidence that genuinely exists: a timeline when the visible facts carry dates spanning real time (weighted higher when the user has selected event/calendar types); grouping by type when several kinds of thing are mixed; the hubs when the view is crowded AND hub-shaped; grouping by source when the facts came from several documents. Every suggestion carries its evidence, shown and not implied. Dismiss once and it never returns." ;
               kpred:principle    "A suggestion must be EARNED BY THE DATA. Silence is the correct and common answer — six of the nineteen tests assert that we say nothing." ;
               kpred:principle    "At most ONE suggestion. A menu of five things to try is not help, it is homework — and it is how a helpful feature becomes one the user mutes." ;
               kpred:principle    "Show the evidence, never imply it. 'Trust me' is not a reason." ;
               kpred:known-issue  "FIXED 2026-07-12 — ViewAdjust.layout omitted 'timeline' and 'hierarchy' while KnowledgeGraph supported them, so SHELLY COULD NOT REQUEST A TIMELINE LAYOUT AT ALL: the single most obvious thing to offer someone staring at dated facts. A view-control API that cannot express the view is not an API. Now typed from the one GraphLayout union both sides share." .

# == THE MISSION — arrived at 2026-07-13, and worth not losing ==================
# "It's never about the tool, it's about the knowledge."
#
# The problem is not storage and it is not search. It is that the knowledge needed to
# DECIDE something is usually a few team members away — which is a DISTANCE problem, not
# an information problem. The knowledge exists. It is three hops of social latency away,
# and every hop costs a meeting, a thread, a week.
#
# Full text fails at this for a specific reason: A DOCUMENT RECORDS CONCLUSIONS, NOT THE
# STRUCTURE THAT PRODUCED THEM. You can read a design doc and still not know which
# constraint was load-bearing, which option was already rejected and why, or which number
# in it was measured rather than guessed. Two documents cannot be diffed for REASONING.
# Two graphs can.
#
# And the honest, hard part: the most decision-relevant knowledge is usually the stuff
# NOBODY WROTE DOWN, held by someone who does not know it is load-bearing. Nobody writes
# "we tried that in 2019 and it broke because the vendor's clock drifted" — not because it
# is secret, but because to the person holding it, it is not a fact, it is just obvious.
# A knowledge graph cannot extract what nobody thought to say. Pretending otherwise would
# be its own overclaim.
#
# WHICH IS WHY THE INVENTION IS NOT WHAT THE GRAPH STORES. IT IS WHAT THE GRAPH CAN HOLD
# THE SHAPE OF WHEN IT IS MISSING.
#
# A partial fact — subject and predicate known, object '?', and here is what it BLOCKS —
# is not a limitation of the model. It is the most useful node in the graph. It says:
# there is a hole here, this is its exact shape, and four things are stalled behind it.
#
# Because the reason the knowledge is "a few team members away" is not that you cannot
# reach them. IT IS THAT YOU DO NOT KNOW WHAT TO ASK. You cannot walk to someone's desk
# with a question you have not yet discovered you have. A graph that can hold a WELL-FORMED
# ABSENCE turns "go find out what we are missing" into "answer this one question, and four
# blocked things unblock".

kb:mission rdf:type            ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "The mission" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:reckons-ai ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:thesis ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:partial-facts ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:async-orchestration ;
               kpred:description  "It is never about the tool. It is about the knowledge — and specifically about the knowledge you need to DECIDE, which is usually a few team members away. That is a distance problem, not an information problem." ;
               kpred:principle    "A document records CONCLUSIONS, not the structure that produced them. Two documents cannot be diffed for reasoning; two graphs can." ;
               kpred:principle    "The most decision-relevant knowledge is the stuff nobody wrote down, held by someone who does not know it is load-bearing. A graph CANNOT extract what nobody thought to say — and claiming otherwise would be its own overclaim." ;
               kpred:principle    "THE INVENTION IS NOT WHAT THE GRAPH STORES. It is that the graph can hold the SHAPE OF WHAT IS MISSING. A well-formed absence — subject and predicate known, object unknown, and here is what it blocks — is the most useful node in the graph." ;
               kpred:principle    "You cannot ask a question you have not discovered you have. The value of a partial fact is that it turns 'go find out what we are missing' into 'answer this one question, and four blocked things unblock'." ;
               kpred:principle    "A fact without its evidence — its excerpt, its diagram, its measurement — is a conclusion. It cannot be checked by anyone who was not there, which is everyone who matters." ;
               kpred:principle    "Detection is an arms race; provenance is durable. Every forensic tell you publish becomes a term in the next model's objective. Attribution to an accountable party does not get outrun by better generators, because it was never about how convincing the artifact is." .

kb:tenet-absence rdf:type      ktype:Tenet ;
               rdfs:label   "The most useful thing a graph can hold is a well-formed absence." ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:thesis ;
               kpred:show-on-landing "true" ;
               kpred:tenet-status "built" ;
               hnav:order   3 ;
               kpred:tenet-body   "You cannot ask a question you have not discovered you have. So a fact whose object is still unknown is not a gap in the graph — it is the point of it. Subject known, predicate known, object still open, and four things stalled behind it. That turns 'go find out what we are missing' into 'answer this one question'. The knowledge you need to decide is usually a few people away; the hard part was never reaching them, it was knowing what to ask." .

# Self-hostable integrations to round out the open-source stack (raised 2026-07-10).
# The n8n contact form (F20) is the template; these extend the same "visual in-app,
# side-effects via self-hosted service" pattern to home automation + a self-hosted
# cloud. All should land via the Integration Plugin SDK (F61), not bespoke wiring.

kb:int-homeassistant rdf:type ktype:Tool ;
               rdfs:label   "Home Assistant" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F62" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:provides     "home automation (self-hosted)" ;
               kpred:description  "Integrate the popular self-hostable home-automation platform. Two directions: ingest HA entities/states/automations as graph facts (a queryable model of the home), and trigger HA automations from the graph (via HA's REST/websocket API or an n8n bridge). Self-hostable, local-first — fits the thesis. Rounds out the self-hosted integration set alongside n8n + Nextcloud." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:n8n-cloud-sync ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:integration-plugin-sdk .

kb:int-nextcloud rdf:type    ktype:Tool ;
               rdfs:label   "Nextcloud" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F63" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:provides     "self-hosted files / calendar / contacts" ;
               kpred:description  "Integrate Nextcloud — the self-hostable cloud for files, calendar (CalDAV), and contacts (CardDAV). Two high-value roles: (a) a SELF-HOSTED folder-sync target — the local-first alternative to Google Drive (F56) for graphs + assets; and (b) calendar/contacts ingest, complementing Indico (also self-hostable). Uses the same two-way reconcile as folder sync via the Integration Plugin SDK's storage capability." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:drive-folder-sync ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:int-indico ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:integration-plugin-sdk .

kb:cloud-automation-providers rdf:type ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "Cloud automation providers (future)" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:description  "n8n (self-hosted, open-source) is the primary automation backend; the same contact-form / webhook pattern generalises to CLOUD automation providers for users who prefer managed services — Zapier, Microsoft Power Automate (M365), and others. Each becomes a webhook/connector plug-in under the Integration Plugin SDK (F61); the app posts the same payloads regardless of provider. Self-hosted n8n stays the default for the offline-first, no-SaaS stance." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:n8n-cloud-sync ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:integration-plugin-sdk .

