# -- Design System (shadcn-svelte) -----------------------------------------------

# -- F29: Currents — streamed ingest & the Pod view -------------------------------
# Planned 2026-07-02, refined same day. Ocean naming: a "current" is a configured
# recurring stream (RSS/site/topic) attached to a specific graph; "the pod" is the
# graph view mode where arrivals swim in. News is the first use case, not the only
# one (research-tool tracking, topic monitoring). Decisions: n8n-primary crawl with
# browser fallback; in-app graph delivery (no published feed); type gate on NEW
# entity creation only; settings as meta triples in the graph; arrivals always
# pending-review, previewed translucently in the pod.

kb:currents    rdf:type      ktype:Feature ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/currents.test.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/currents-persist.test.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/current-ranking.test.ts" ;
               rdfs:label    "Currents — Streamed Ingest & Pod View" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F29" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:description  "Recurring external content streams (currents) that merge into a graph through the existing add/merge/review spine. Each arrival becomes pending facts: a document/article node plus extracted concept nodes with provenance links. Personalization is the graph itself: headlines ranked by embedding affinity to the graph's entities. The pod is a graph view mode where pending arrivals render translucent and drifting until accepted. Ground News has no official public API (verified 2026-07-02) — speculative; reliable inputs are RSS/Atom, GDELT, keyed news APIs, Open-Meteo for weather context." ;
               kpred:principle    "Add, merge, and review are the base spine — currents never bypass them. Personalization data (location, interests) stays local-first; the VPS only fetches public feeds." ;
               kpred:naming       "Feature/streams: currents. Graph view mode: the pod (whale-themed accents, consistent with Shelly and the Liquid ocean aesthetic). Avoid: feed (overused), crawl (technical)." ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:currents-phase-1 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:currents-phase-2 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:currents-phase-3 ;
               kpred:has-phase    kb:currents-phase-4 ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:source-refresh ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:n8n-cloud-sync ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:local-offload ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:source-subscription ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:condition-triggers ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:content-safety .

kb:currents-settings rdf:type ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label    "Graph-level currents settings (meta triples)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "Per-graph configuration stored as urn:reckons:meta/currents/* statements in the graph itself — portable with TTL export/import, visible to MCP tools, hidden from graph edges via isMetaPredicate. Holds: the current definitions (source URL/kind/cadence/label), the entity-type gate (enable/disable NEW entity creation per ktype — e.g. a research graph admits only Tool and Concept), and location/interest markers for ranking. Facts attaching to entities already in the graph always flow through (pending review); only new-entity creation is gated." .

kb:currents-phase-1 rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "F29.1 — Currents model & type gate" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:description  "Meta-triples settings module (read/write urn:reckons:meta/currents/*), the entity-type gate enforced where stream-originated batches enter addStatements, and the arrival provenance model (article/document node + extracted concepts + derived-from links). Pure model + gate, no UI. SHIPPED 2026-07-02: src/lib/rdf/currents.ts (settings round-trip, isTypeAllowed, applyTypeGate, buildArrivalStatements), origin-aware gate in addStatements (kb.svelte.ts), currents namespace registered in isMetaPredicate; 14 unit tests." .

kb:currents-phase-2 rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "F29.2 — Fetch: n8n Currents Monitor + browser fallback" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:currents-phase-1 ;
               kpred:has-workflow kb:n8n-currents-monitor ;
               kpred:description  "n8n workflow (extends the Source Monitor pattern): scheduled polling of RSS/Atom feeds and watched pages every 30 minutes respecting each current's cadenceMinutes, dedupes items by URL into a data table, app syncs down and pushes arrivals through the type gate. Direct browser fetch fallback (fetchCurrentDirect) for CORS-friendly feeds, with a clear CORS-flavoured error otherwise. Ranking: BGE-small embedding affinity between item text and the graph's top-degree entities; near-duplicate collapse via cosine clustering; content-policy filter drops blocked items pre-rank. SHIPPED 2026-07-03: n8n workflow qb9uPZ8GScAmuUOX (Reckons Currents Monitor) live-tested against https://hnrss.org/frontpage — real items fetched, deduped, and served back via webhook. App side: src/lib/integrations/n8n/currents-sync.ts (registerCurrent, fetchCurrentItems, fetchCurrentDirect, processArrivals — builds the article node only, skips full extraction on the unattended sweep since it's too heavy; deeper extraction stays a manual, on-demand step from the review UI), src/lib/rdf/current-ranking.ts (rankItems, topEntityLabels). settings.n8nBaseUrl added (reused by both F20 cloud sync and F29.2). 26 unit tests (RSS/Atom fixtures, mocked embeddings, mocked fetch, mocked addStatements)." .

kb:currents-phase-3 rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "F29.3 — The Pod view & settings UI" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:currents-phase-1 ;
               kpred:description  "Pod mode in the graph view: pending arrivals render translucent and drifting (reuse the ghost-graph rendering machinery) with accept/dismiss directly on the node; whale-themed accents. Currents settings UI on the graph management page: define currents, toggle entity types, set location. Context blocks: weather via Open-Meteo (free, no key), in-your-state-yesterday via location-filtered items. Daily briefing summarized via prefer-local Ollama. STARTED 2026-07-02: pod toggle (whale chip) on the graph page; arrival nodes (pending-only entities) render translucent with a drift-bob and sky-blue dashed halo in KnowledgeGraph2D. SHIPPED 2026-07-03: accept/dismiss actions on the node panel when pod mode is on and the selected node is an unaccepted arrival (setStatus→confirmed/rejected across all pending statements touching that node) — src/routes/(app)/+page.svelte, with a small additive onarrivalstatus callback exposed from KnowledgeGraph2D.svelte; currents settings UI on the /kb graph-management page — define/edit/remove currents (slug auto-derived from label), kind select (rss/url/topic), cadence, enabled toggle, entity-type gate as toggle chips (registered types from entity-types.svelte.ts; empty = all allowed), and a location field — src/routes/(app)/kb/+page.svelte, persisted via a new replaceCurrentsSettings() helper in src/lib/rdf/currents-persist.ts (diffs against existing urn:reckons:meta/currents/* statements: rejects removed entries, revives identical-but-previously-rejected entries, adds new ones; settings statements stay status confirmed); 6 unit tests on the pure diff function. REFINED 2026-07-04: the floating pod toggle chip was removed from the graph view (user feedback: disliked the button); pod view is now enabled via a '🐋 pod view' toggle in the currents section of the Graph tab (/kb), backed by a per-device localStorage preference (src/lib/stores/pod-view.svelte.ts, podViewEnabled/setPodViewEnabled). The graph view reads the shared store and shows a small read-only '🐋 pod' status indicator (not a button) when on. Rationale: pod is a currents feature, so its controls live with currents settings on the Graph tab. Remaining: context blocks (weather, in-your-state-yesterday) and the daily briefing summary." .

kb:currents-phase-4 rdf:type ktype:Phase ;
               rdfs:label    "F29.4 — External integrations" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:currents ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:currents-phase-2 ;
               kpred:description  "Connectors beyond RSS: GDELT (free, no key), NewsAPI/NewsData/GNews (user-supplied keys, BYO-key pattern). Ground News: no official public developer API (verified 2026-07-02; only third-party wrappers) — revisit if one ships; bias/blindspot data would map onto source-trust triples." .

# -- F30: Review Workbench -------------------------------------------------------

kb:review-workbench rdf:type  ktype:Feature ;
                    kpred:tested-by    "tests/e2e/review.test.ts" ;
               rdfs:label    "Review Workbench — browse while reviewing" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F30" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "Rework the review screen into a full graph workbench: all graph view controls (layout toggles, node search) available on the preview; node details panel on the left with chat below it; the review queue on the right keeps per-item approve/reject/chat actions. Selecting a review item drives the graph (camera fly + selection + name caption + edge highlight). v1 shipped 2026-07-03: clicking an incoming card flies the preview camera to the subject node via the focusKey prop on KnowledgeGraph2D, left-border highlight on the focused card, node-name badge over the graph. v2 shipped 2026-07-03: browse controls (free/focus/hub layout ToggleGroup + a filter-to-highlight node search box) added to the preview's graph pane; a compact node-details panel floats on the left of the graph when a node is selected, showing its label, type, and facts (pending ones tagged), with a scoped chat box below it that seeds the existing Shelly chat (requestShellyChat/TurtleChatPanel) with the node's context rather than a new chat stack; click-to-focus (camera fly + accent border) extended to the deletions, merges, and align tab cards via the same focusStatement path; KnowledgeGraph2D gained an additive highlightedEdges prop that draws the exact incoming triple's edge in bright gold, distinct from the existing orange selection ring. Remaining: none tracked — future polish only (e.g. highlighting the specific edge for deletion/merge suggestions, which aren't currently drawn as graph edges)." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:knowledge-graph ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:currents .

# -- F31: Local Model Benchmarking & Orchestration -------------------------------

kb:local-model-bench rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Local Model Benchmarking & Orchestration" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F31" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:in-dev       "2026-07-07"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/visual/run-vlm-gate-bench.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/bench/run-coding-bench.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/bench/run-agentic-bench.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/bench/run-cost-bench.ts" ;
               kpred:description  "Evidence-driven selection of LOCAL models for agent grunt work: keep the strong cloud model (Opus) on the main/orchestration thread and delegate bulk work to local Ollama models via `ollama launch` integrations (claude/opencode/etc.) on a local multi-GPU Ollama host — zero API cost, private. Two reproducible benchmarks pick the right local model per role. (1) VLM visual-gate bench — tests/visual/run-vlm-gate-bench.ts + vlm-golden.ts — scores local vision models as 'does this appear' gates against human-verified screenshot labels (10 images, 48 checks across 7 capability types: toast/mobile/graph/blank/settings/kb/align-tab); the gate score weights recall highest (a miss waves a real regression through — the one intolerable error) plus precision, accuracy, and latency. A cheap local VLM screens every screenshot; only its flags escalate to the expensive reviewer (Opus/Claude Vision). Result: qwen2.5vl:7b selected (94%, 0 misses); granite3.2-vision brittle (44%, 2 misses) despite a perfect 6/6 smoke test — a caution against trusting smoke tests; moondream is prose-only and unusable for yes/no gating. (2) Coding-correctness bench — tests/bench/run-coding-bench.ts + coding-golden.ts — self-contained edit/implement/fix/parse tasks graded by writing the model's code block to a temp dir and running an assert driver via tsx (pass@1 + latency + tokens + output cleanliness). Result: qwen3-coder selected (4/4, fastest full-passer, terse); devstral-small-2 and gpt-oss:20b also 4/4; the large general model nemotron3:33b was the worst coder here (3/4, slowest, ~10x tokens) — reserve big reasoning models for planning, not code grunt work. Operational lesson baked into both harnesses: local models default to very large context windows (up to 128k) which balloon KV-cache VRAM and can crash larger vision runtimes under contention, so the benches pin a small num_ctx (sized to hold one screenshot / prompt) and unload each model between runs. SHIPPED 2026-07-07. Phase 2 SHIPPED 2026-07-07: tool-loop agentic coding bench — tests/bench/run-agentic-bench.ts + agentic-tasks.ts — drives each local model through a real tool-calling loop (list_files/read_file/write_file/run_tests/finish) in a sandbox, measuring pass@1, turns, self-verification, scope discipline, and spiral rate. Result: devstral-small-2 top (0.98, all pass, fewest turns, ~366 tokens), qwen3-coder and gpt-oss:20b also perfect; nemotron3:33b failed a third time (33% pass, spiraled, 6225 tokens, self-verified once) — consistent across all three benches that big reasoning models are wrong for coding/agentic grunt work. Cost bench SHIPPED 2026-07-07: tests/bench/run-cost-bench.ts + cost-golden.ts — compares Opus-token cost of full-system vs Opus-alone on graph-grounded generation, three arms (A0 Opus+raw graph, A1 Opus+kb_compress-style compressed subgraph, A2 local drafts + Opus reviews), inferring $ from live API usage. Result (Opus 4.8, ~$0.48 spend): A1 and A2 both 79% cheaper than A0 at identical 100% quality — the graph compression is the dominant lever (6x fewer input tokens); local delegation adds little on short outputs and pays only when OUTPUT is large (Opus output tokens at $25/Mtok are the expensive ones). Extended 2026-07-07: a long-form (~700-word) generation task confirmed the delegation win — A2 (local writes, Opus reviews/approves) 77% cheaper than A0 vs A1's 66%, because the expensive OUTPUT is generated free locally; and raw context proved LOWER quality here — the full raw graph scored 60% fact-coverage vs 80% for the compressed subgraph (needle-in-haystack). Capacity note: the whole static graph is ~116k tokens — fits comfortably in Opus's 1M window, but feeding it raw costs ~50x more per query than a compressed subgraph and can ground worse; compression is a cost+quality lever, not a capacity workaround. Harness comparison (OpenCode, Qwen Code): both are built for interactive use and their headless local-model paths are immature — OpenCode ships no local-Ollama provider (only ollama-cloud; needs manual provider config), Qwen Code defaults to qwen-oauth cloud — observed opening a browser to chat.qwen.ai for login even in headless -p mode — and even wired neither completed a trivial fix headlessly in 120s via the OpenAI-compatible /v1 path (~13s cold per call), whereas the minimal custom tool-loop and Claude Code complete the same tasks in seconds. Qualitative conclusion (matching hands-on experience): Claude Code's harness has materially lower friction/overhead for local-model agent work; a clean headless pass-rate comparison would need long timeouts and per-tool auth/config work not yet done." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:mcp-server ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:ci-cd-kb-watch .

# -- F32: Partial Facts & Answer-Flow-Back ---------------------------------------

kb:partial-facts rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Partial Facts & Answer-Flow-Back" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F32" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/partial-facts.test.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/partial-facts.ts" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:mission ;
               kpred:description  "A triple whose object is unknown: subject and predicate asserted, object '?', needsObject true. The Review tab renders an entity picker instead of accept/reject; answering it writes back to knowledge.answers.jsonl where the agent that asked resumes. A question now also carries WHAT IT BLOCKS and WHO ASKED, so the graph can answer the question that matters — not 'what don't we know?' (a list of holes, demoralizing and unactionable) but 'what would answering THIS unblock?'. questionsByImpact ranks open questions by how much they free up, breaking ties toward the OLDER question, because a hole nobody has filled in a week is evidence nobody will fill it by accident." ;
               kpred:principle    "A partial fact is not a gap in the model. IT IS THE POINT OF IT. You cannot ask a question you have not discovered you have (kb:mission)." ;
               kpred:principle    "A question with a price gets answered; one without does not. Always state what it blocks." ;
               kpred:known-issue  "FIXED 2026-07-13 — THE FEATURE THE MISSION RESTS ON HAD NO TESTS, and two fields were being DROPPED on import. (1) `blocks` was discarded, so the graph knew it had a hole but not what the hole COST — which is the difference between a to-do and a priority, and it is the entire 'answer this one question and four blocked things unblock' value. The landing page was already claiming it worked. (2) `askedBy` was discarded, so an answer came back unattributed and could not be claimed by the agent waiting on it — which breaks the moment more than one agent is running. Both now survive drainWorkspacePending; DiffEntry builds the answer via resolvePartial() so the wiring cannot silently rot again." ;
               kpred:known-issue  "GUARDED: computeDiff must never structurally diff a partial fact. Diffing '?' against an existing object compares a HOLE to a VALUE and produces a bogus conflict or refinement — the user would be asked to adjudicate nonsense. Now covered by a test." .

# -- F33: Release Pipeline & Branch Alignment ------------------------------------

kb:release-pipeline rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/bench/scoring.test.ts" ;
               rdfs:label    "Release Pipeline & Branch Alignment" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F33" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:in-dev       "2026-07-07"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:description  "Model the release pipeline in the graphs and check branches against it. Three environments with review gates (static/reckons-production.ttl): kb:env-dev (branch dev, DEVELOPER technical review), kb:env-staging (branch staging, STAKEHOLDER business review), kb:env-production (branch main, both approvals; deploys on push). Features carry promotion predicates: kpred:in-dev / kpred:in-staging / kpred:in-production (dated), plus kpred:dev-approved / kpred:stakeholder-approved sign-offs; has-status 'production' implies in-production. scripts/branch-align.ts parses these claims and compares them to real git state (branch existence, main..branch merged PRs), reporting the pipeline per environment and flagging drift: features marked in-dev but status 'production' (contradiction), 'functional' features not marked in any env (untracked), in-dev features already on main (should promote to production status), missing env branches, and merged PRs on a branch not reflected by any tracked feature (unplanned). Run: npm run branch-align. Complements the code<->Graph alignment in scripts/kb-align.ts (F26) by adding the environment/branch dimension. Development lifecycle — each gate reviews against a graph: (1) BUSINESS DEFINITION of the feature in the roadmap graph (business-goal level, stakeholder-owned); (2) developer + Opus orchestrate the technical spec in the CODEBASE graph; (3) local agents do the task work; (4) PR to dev; (5) DEVELOPER gate — collaborative review of the dev deploy (dev.reckons-ai.pages.dev) with visual-testing agents (VLM), confirming the implementation against the codebase graph -> kpred:dev-approved; (6) merge to staging; (7) STAKEHOLDER gate — business review on staging.reckons-ai.pages.dev of the built feature against the ORIGINAL roadmap goal (does the result meet the intent) -> kpred:stakeholder-approved; (8) agent-assisted DOCUMENTATION generation, reviewed by the stakeholder; (9) merge to main (production, reckons.ai). Env nodes carry kpred:deploy-url and kpred:reviews-graph (dev->codebase technical spec, staging->roadmap business intent); production requires-documentation." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:ci-cd-kb-watch ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:git-analysis ;
               kpred:enforcement-gap "The review gates are MODELED in the graph but NOT ENFORCED on GitHub (audited 2026-07-11: main, dev, AND staging have branch-protection objects with NOTHING enforced — no required PR reviews, no required status checks, enforce_admins off, force-pushes allowed). Demonstrated live: a merge intended for dev landed on MAIN and deployed to production with no gate stopping it (the base-branch re-target silently failed and nothing blocked the merge). Constraint: only ONE collaborator (Data-Insight-Solutions), so GitHub required-human-approval would deadlock solo merges (can't approve your own PR)." ;
               kpred:enforcement-plan "DECISION 2026-07-11: allow merges for NOW (velocity during massive change); ENFORCE at LAUNCH (public announcement of Reckons.AI), once the review process is smooth and fully tested. Near-term scope: main only. At launch, enable branch protection on main (then dev + staging): require PR + required status checks green (Type check + Unit tests + Build, Reckons.AI Graph Alignment Check, E2E (Desktop Chrome), Deploy Gate — Graph Render Smoke) with strict/up-to-date, and enforce_admins ON (no bypass) — the automated F33 CI gates become the enforced review. Add required human approval once a 2nd reviewer / review bot exists. INTERIM GUARDRAIL (behavioral, agents): always target dev, verify a PR's resolved base branch BEFORE merging, never merge to main without explicit production intent — so an intended-dev merge can't hit production again." .

kb:deep-testing rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Deep Testing & Living Coverage" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F34" ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:in-dev       "2026-07-09"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:description  "PHASE 1 SHIPPED (2026-07-09): offline exhaustive button crawler — scripts/offline/button-crawl.ts (npm run test:crawl). Clicks every interactive element on every route and, per click, records crashes (console/page errors), blank screens (solid-fill pixel artifact via tests/visual/vision-local), SILENT NO-OPS (nothing observable changed — URL / node count / graph id / open panels / title / visible-text hash; the class the docs-hub leap regression fell into, which a crash-only crawler misses), and sub-44px touch targets. Resets to the route before each click for deterministic per-click state. Offline-first: pixel/DOM/touch checks are pure local JS (no Ollama/Opus); findings queued to knowledge.pending.jsonl for review. TIED TO THE GRAPH: the crawl also emits a TestWorkflow -> TestStep STORY graph (tests/visual/button-crawl.ttl — one workflow per route, one step per click, each carrying its screenshot via kmeta:gif and a kpred:result verdict + kpred:violates rubric citations), so results are reviewable in-app as an ordered story rather than a JSON dump (same schema as the navigation-sweep story; written to a sibling file so it never clobbers the separately-generated visual-tests.ttl). NEXT: VLM visual scoring of screenshots against kb:web-uiux-rubric across the device matrix (phase 2); a persistent-context / warm-service-worker pass to catch stale-cache regressions fresh contexts never reproduce (phase 3); Opus authoring new path specs from coverage gaps (phase 4). --- FULL DESIGN: An OFFLINE, ever-growing use-case test system distinct from the fast per-build suite. (1) Deep tests are PREDETERMINED end-user PATHS through the web app, run LOCALLY on demand — not on every build; the per-build suite stays fast (unit + smoke). (2) Two evaluation dimensions beyond pass/fail: a VISUAL surface (each path is captured across a DEVICE MATRIX via Playwright device descriptors — phones + tablets: iPhone 15, Pixel 7, iPad Pro 11 are already configured in playwright.config.ts as touch-emulated projects, extensible to more; a local VLM then scores the per-device screenshots against the Web/Mobile UI-UX Rubric, so responsive/touch guidelines are checked at real viewport sizes — scalable emulation that complements spot-checks on physical iPhone/iPad) and a TEXT/output-consumption surface (generated answer/output quality — leads with the conclusion, scannable, grounded). (3) The rubric is a graph: reckons-workspace design-principles graph (kb:web-uiux-rubric) — testable guidelines grounded in core design principles; every finding CITES the violated guideline (kpred:derives-from -> core principle). Mobile-tagged guidelines gate the responsive work. (4) Opus orchestration periodically ANALYZES coverage, finds GAPS, and authors new path specs at various times (not every build); paths are graph entities so the library grows. (5) Novel user workflows: the app transparently benches and KINDLY ASKS the user to opt in to contributing their real workflow as a new test path (consent-based, never covert). (6) Runs as an offline procedure (scripts/offline/), emitting gaps + rubric violations as pending questions for review in Reckons.AI. Builds on visual-testing (VLM gate) and relates to the release pipeline's developer gate. Consumes the offline-first / Opus-orchestrates-online model." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:visual-testing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:release-pipeline .

kb:steering-committee rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Steering Committee (Enterprise)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F35" ;
