               kpred:principle    "Read-only is the default posture for now; editing is opt-in per environment." ;
               kpred:description  "Route CMS commits to the right branch per environment, and map edit KIND to the approval it needs. DONE (per-environment routing, static/admin/index.html): production (reckons.ai and the pages.dev apex) is left to auto-init from config.yml (branch: main) untouched; only the dev branch alias and hashed preview subdomains (*.reckons-ai.pages.dev) take Sveltia manual-init (window.CMS_MANUAL_INIT + CMS.init with load_config_file: true) and override backend.branch to 'dev', so edits made while testing the review flow land on dev, not production main. Verified: the pinned @sveltia/cms@0.169.1 bundle exposes CMS.init and honours CMS_MANUAL_INIT; the host->branch selector is a pure, unit-tested function (reckonsAdminBranch); production path is unchanged. Remaining smoke test: a real dev-login confirms load_config_file merges (collections preserved) and a commit lands on dev. FUTURE: (1) per-content/section mapping (which collections route where); (2) tie edit KIND to approval — trivial human polish self-approves on main (see principle), structural/graph changes flow through F33 gates + F44 change notes; (3) optionally derive the branch from CF_PAGES_BRANCH at build time instead of hostname matching. Relates to F27 publishing, F33 release pipeline, F44 change notes." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:release-pipeline ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:change-notes .

# -- Graph-as-Site-Navigation (F49) --------------------------------------------
# The published site's map IS the graph: WebPage nodes appear as graph nodes, a
# landing page + subpage nav is defined and edited in-graph, and nav edges use a
# MUCH lighter force so a nav hub linking many pages doesn't distort the graph.

kb:graph-as-navigation rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Graph-as-Site-Navigation" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F49" ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/edge-force.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/edge-force.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "The part the roadmap flags CRITICAL — per-edge-kind force weights — is built and tested (6 tests, 2026-07-15). edge-force.ts classifies a predicate as concept / nav / page and returns a spring-weight multiplier (concept 1, nav 0.15, page 0.1), so a densely-linked site hub pulls far more weakly than concept edges and cannot warp the knowledge layout. isSiteEdge() marks structure edges for a secondary layout pass. Pure/deterministic. SCAFFOLDED not functional: the force simulation does not yet CALL edgeForceWeight (the 2D/3D graph still springs every edge equally), WebPage nodes do not yet render as graph nodes, and in-graph page-metadata editing is not built. This is the enabler, not the feature." ;
               kpred:principle    "The graph is the PRIMARY navigation of what pages are published and where they're accessed — not a separate site-map UI. Publishing structure lives in, and is edited from, the graph." ;
               kpred:description  "Make published pages first-class citizens of the graph so the graph itself is the site map. PARTS: (1) WebPage nodes (ktype:WebPage, F27) RENDER as graph nodes — visible alongside concepts, distinguishable (icon/type), selectable. (2) In-graph site structure: define a LANDING/home page and navigation to SUBPAGES as graph edges (reuse skos:broader for parent/child + nav:next/prev for sequence, the same hierarchy vocabulary the hnav trees use), created and rearranged in the graph. (3) LIGHT-FORCE nav edges — CRITICAL: page/nav edges must carry a much lower force-directed spring weight than concept edges, because a nav hub connected to many published pages (or pages linked across every concept) would otherwise collapse/warp the main graph shape. Introduce per-edge-kind force weights (concept edges normal; page/nav edges very light, or excluded from the main force pass and laid out in a secondary/orbit pass) so adding the whole published site never distorts the knowledge layout. (4) In-graph PAGE METADATA editing: edit slug, section, template, status, title from the node panel (writes the urn:kbase:page/* triples; round-trips via F27 site-export + md-align). (5) Publishing map: from any concept, see which pages reference/derive from it and jump to them; from a page node, open the published /docs URL. Builds on F27 graph publishing and relates to F46 (question-context pages, another in-graph page attach), the 2D/3D graph (per-edge force weights), and the /docs route." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:knowledge-graph ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:question-context-pages .

# -- Import & Workspace UX Rework (F50) ----------------------------------------
# The current import + workspace/graph-settings flow is confusing: graph-scoped
# actions live in global Settings, "sync" (write) vs "import" (read) are easy to
# mix up, and a bare-.ttl import silently drops assets. Rework around the graph.

kb:import-workspace-ux rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Import & Workspace UX Rework" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F50" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:description  "Fix the confusing import + workspace/graph-settings experience (user feedback 2026-07-09: 'how horrible the import and workspace/graph settings are right now'). PROBLEMS: (a) graph-data actions (import graphs from folder, sync) live in GLOBAL Settings, far from where graphs are managed; (b) the nav item labeled 'graph' goes to /kb (registry) while the graph VIEW is / — so 'graph settings' has no obvious home; (c) 'sync all graphs now' (WRITE: browser graphs -> folder) reads as the same thing as 'import graphs from folder' (READ: folder -> browser), and the count/'3 graphs' compounds the confusion; (d) importing a bare .ttl silently loses binary assets (icons/previews/models) — folder import restores them (partly addressed: an import-time warning now points to folder import). DIRECTION: (1) surface graph import/export ON the graph page (/kb) where graphs are managed — the user's choice — keeping detailed workspace CONFIG in Settings; (2) clearly separate and label the two DIRECTIONS (push-to-folder vs pull-from-folder) with plain wording and per-direction affordances; (3) make import asset-aware (prefer conventional kbs/{name}/ folders that carry assets; warn on loose/bare .ttl); (4) reconsider naming ('graph' nav vs graph view). Relates to F48 (Sveltia edit routing, the other workspace-branch surface), F27 publishing, and the recursive folder-discovery fix. Small deterministic wins land first; the fuller IA rework is scoped here." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:sveltia-edit-mapping ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:graph-publishing .

# -- Review-Anchored Generation (F51) ------------------------------------------
# The product thesis, stated (2026-07-09). RAG retrieves slivers from large text
# because knowledge is TRAPPED in prose. Invert it: store REVIEWED facts, and
# generate whatever prose a context needs, on demand. Review the compression;
# generate the expansion.

kb:review-anchored-generation rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Review-Anchored Generation" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F51" ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/generation-grounding.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/generation-grounding.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "The MOAT — the grounding CONSTRAINT — is built and tested (9 tests, 2026-07-15), which is the half that matters (the description says so: 'the moat is the grounding constraint, not the generation'). generation-grounding.ts validateGeneration() enforces the render-step contract: every generated sentence must cite >=1 statement, every citation must exist, and at least one must be CONFIRMED — uncited (hallucination), dangling, and unconfirmed citations are each caught. It is the generation-side analog of kb:passage-grounding (grounding.ts, ingest side). Pure/deterministic: it verifies the citation contract, not the paraphrase (that stays a model's job). SCAFFOLDED not functional: the actual grounded GENERATOR (emit prose WITH per-sentence citations) is not built, and nothing wires this validator into the doc/page/tooltip render paths yet — so today it enforces a contract no producer emits." ;
               kpred:principle    "The graph of reviewed facts is the scarce, canonical input; text (docs, pages, prose) is a cheap, disposable, context-tailored OUTPUT generated from it. Store and review facts, not prose." ;
               kpred:principle    "Every generated sentence MUST trace back to a confirmed triple. Generation that invents a claim not in the graph reintroduces hallucination at the render step — the inversion only works married to grounded generation + provenance (ETHICS_PREAMBLE, Shelly's 'only from your triples')." ;
               kpred:principle    "Not all knowledge compresses to clean triples (tone, hedges, the 'because'). That irreducible nuance is what change-notes hold: canonical facts (fully regenerable) + human prose (the nuance that can't be re-derived)." ;
               kpred:description  "Make the RAG-inversion the explicit architecture thesis and hold the system to it: one reviewed fact renders to a tooltip, a paragraph, a warning, a page, a PR description — near-infinite surface, one reviewed source. Builds on context-compression (F25, the compress pipeline) and graph-publishing (F27, graph -> pages); the irreducible-nuance case is change-notes (F44). The moat is the grounding constraint, not the generation." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:context-compression ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:change-notes .

# -- Control Model (F52) -------------------------------------------------------
# Control is the product. Alignment is a smoke detector, not a thermostat; the
# human holds the fact-edit right; divergence between graphs is often intentional
# focus, not error; adoption cost is paid down via familiar outputs.

kb:control-model rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Control Model — the agent-edit boundary" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F52" ;
               kpred:has-status   "scaffolded" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/agent-edit-boundary.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/agent-edit-boundary.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof        "The boundary is now EXPRESSED AS CODE, not just convention (2026-07-15, 6 tests). agent-edit-boundary.ts: gateFactWrite(actor, status) downgrades any agent attempt to settle a fact (confirmed/refined) to a proposal, one-directional and fail-safe (an agent write is never left settled); humans pass through untouched (they hold the fact-edit right); agentTargetPolicy() encodes facts=propose, plan/code/roadmap=direct (git+PR is their review). ENFORCED at the agent write path: addStatements gained origin 'agent', and drainAndImportPending declares it, so the MCP pending drain runs every status through the wall. Composes with F88 (F52 routes to review; F88's competentGate clears it). SCAFFOLDED not functional: today a no-op in practice (the agent paths already write 'pending'), so the wall is future-proofing rather than catching a live violation; it is NOT enforced across every agent write path (only the drain), the fact-vs-plan target rule is not yet a hard gate on file writes, and the live behaviour is not observed (headless)." ;
               kpred:principle    "Alignment is a TRIGGER for human review, not a goal to optimize. The instant an agent can edit the graph to raise its own alignment score, the score measures nothing (Goodhart). Alignment must summon a human at a discrepancy; it must never auto-resolve or let an agent self-serve." ;
               kpred:principle    "The human holds the fact-edit right. Agents PROPOSE (pending) on knowledge/facts and may edit plan/code/roadmap TTL directly — that boundary is control, and today it is convention, not enforcement. Make it a wall: fact-level agent writes go through review." ;
               kpred:principle    "Divergence between two graphs is often intentional FOCUS, not drift. A 'misalignment' is a question ('these disagree — on purpose?'), never an auto-reconcile." ;
               kpred:principle    "Deliver control seamlessly: keep traditional outputs (web pages, markdown) so switching cost from the traditional method to the knowledge-graph method is near zero. Documentation is one render of the knowledge; implementation accuracy and speed is another." ;
               kpred:description  "The enforced boundary of what an agent may write directly (plan/code) vs. only propose (facts, pending review), with alignment reframed as a discrepancy detector and cross-graph divergence treated as a question. The key differentiating feature. Relates to cross-Graph alignment (F16), git-analysis (F24), the review workflow, change-notes (F44), and the release pipeline (F33)." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:cross-kb-alignment ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:git-analysis ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:change-notes ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:release-pipeline .

# -- Review at Scale / Attention (F53) -----------------------------------------
# Review has an attention budget. Spend it on the few contested decisions, not
# the many obvious facts — or the human auto-accepts and review becomes theatre.

kb:review-attention rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Review at Scale — spotlight the decisions" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F53" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/review-attention.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/lib/rdf/review-pipeline.ts" ;
               kpred:has-file     "src/routes/(app)/review/+page.svelte" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/review-attention.test.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/review-pipeline.test.ts" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/e2e/review.test.ts" ;
               kpred:proof-ui     "WIRED INTO /review AND VERIFIED IN A BROWSER (2026-07-15). buildReviewPlan now drives the incoming tab: an honest headline (reviewPlanSummary), a SPOTLIGHT strip of the contested few (conflicts + open decisions, shown when any exist), and pending facts grouped into per-entity CARDS (F83) with a by-entity/flat toggle — the per-fact confirm/reject controls unchanged, so nothing is hidden. The e2e test seeds a real ingest, opens /review, and asserts the entity cards, the headline, the toggle, and that confirm is still reachable: 6/6 review e2e pass. Remaining (why not 'production'): the tenure-driven-drift signal is not built, and the merge SUGGEST tier is not surfaced in this UI yet." ;
               kpred:composed-of  "review-pipeline.ts buildReviewPlan() is the single front door: dedupe (F80.1) -> route by competence (F88) -> spotlight the contested (F53) -> entity cards (F83). One tested composition, so the UI wires to one function and the stage order lives in one place. Integration-tested end to end (6 tests). Still unwired to the UI." ;
               kpred:proof        "The attention-scoring CORE is built and tested (10 tests, 2026-07-15), layered on F88 routing. spotlightUserQueue() takes the USER lane from routeQueue (what only the human can settle) and splits it: CONFLICTS (findDichotomies, kind 'conflict') and open DECISIONS (F32 partial facts) go to the spotlight; uncontested facts flow to a quiet lane; blast radius nudges the ranking. The spotlight is CAPPED to a manageable few (default 7) and over-cap contested items are HELD BACK, never dumped into quiet — hiding a contested item is the one thing it must not do. attentionScore() is pure and separately tested. SCAFFOLDED not functional: not yet wired into the review surface (the UI still lists everything flat), tenure-driven drift is not yet a signal, and the live surface is not observed." ;
               kpred:principle    "Granularity breeds rubber-stamping. A review list that is too fine trains the human to 'accept all' — condense decisions to a manageable few at a time." ;
               kpred:principle    "Spend attention on disagreement, not agreement. Fresh, uncontested facts should flow through quietly; CONFLICTS and DECISIONS get the spotlight." ;
               kpred:principle    "Tenure anchors perspective. The longer a graph is worked, the more its established intention frames new facts — adding to an OLD graph pulls new triples toward the old view (drift). Surface that pull; adding fresh triples is not the same as extending an anchored graph." ;
               kpred:description  "Redesign the review surface around the attention budget: condense to a few decisions, promote conflicts/contested changes, quiet the uncontested, and flag tenure-driven drift on an established graph. Onboarding is this same problem at t=0 (see soft-onboarding). Relates to the review workbench (F30) and partial facts (F32)." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:review-workbench ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:partial-facts .

# -- Soft Onboarding (F54) -----------------------------------------------------
# The review-at-scale principle applied to the first run: a few nodes and ONE
# decision, not the concept-dense docs graph. Shipped 2026-07-09 (PR #79).

kb:soft-onboarding rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/stores/__tests__/official-kb.test.ts" ;
               rdfs:label    "Soft Onboarding — the everyday starter graph" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F54" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:in-dev       "2026-07-09"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:description  "The 'Getting started' button loads an everyday graph (static/starter-everyday.ttl — 'This Weekend': two friends who live apart, Alex in San Francisco and Jordan in Los Angeles, choosing a weekend campsite roughly halfway between them in the Eastern Sierra) as CONFIRMED facts, and opens Shelly's guided tour, instead of the 300+ statement concept-dense documentation graph. The graph is modelled with realistic depth: two people (with photos + home cities), two real campgrounds (Lake George, Oh! Ridge) with nightly price / elevation / reservation links, two elevation-specific weather forecasts, four drive routes (each friend's distance + time to each option), and a Fri–Sun calendar window each option is dated against — so the 'time' layout shows which stay fits. The real tension: Jordan wants the pricier, colder, fast-booking alpine option; Oh! Ridge is cheaper, warmer, fits the whole window and is nearly equidistant. The full docs graph is demoted to a quiet secondary link. The F53 principle at t=0. Shipped in PR #79; enriched to realistic depth on the folder-sync branch." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:review-attention ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:knowledge-graph .

# -- Meta Visual Asset Generation (F58) ----------------------------------------
# The VISUAL analog of Review-Anchored Generation (F51): F51 renders reviewed
# facts to PROSE on demand; F58 renders the graph's facts + its embedded VISUAL
# assets (source images, GLBs, icons, previews) into a single new asset — an
# image, a document, or a 3D model. The graph itself is the brief. Raised
# 2026-07-10; feasibility of LOCAL image/3D generation is uncertain (cloud
# providers likely needed first), so this is roadmap-first.

kb:meta-visual-generation rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Meta Visual Asset Generation" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F58" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:principle    "The graph is the brief. The FACTS and the RELATIONSHIPS between an entity's visual assets are the detailed description that drives the generation — a red hex on a node recolors its image; two node images with a 'combine' relationship (or a prompt) merge into one; a subgraph of GLBs assembles into a scene." ;
               kpred:principle    "Creative generation does NOT need the full Situation-Target-Proposal loop. STP is for grounded decisions; making an asset is expression. So generation offers a single free-form prompt AND the option to drop STP prompting entirely for more variety — while still injecting the relevant graph facts as context." ;
               kpred:description  "Collage/compose everything a graph (or selected subgraph) holds — source images, GLB models, 2D icons, preview images — plus the facts and inter-asset relationships, into ONE output asset. Enhanced Reckoning becomes 'a generation of some kind': the output can be a picture, a PDF, or a 3D file rather than a text proposal. Needs a NEW generation backend (no text/image->image capability exists today; 3D exists via Meshy text-to-3d). Local 3D generation feasibility is unknown — flagged for research; Meshy.AI is the likely near-term path to function." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:review-anchored-generation ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:wf-reckon ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:entity-types ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:int-meshy .

