# -- Spatial / Map Force Layout (F59) ------------------------------------------
# A new force mode that positions nodes by real-world LOCATION, not just graph
# relation. Raised 2026-07-10. The existing force modes (free/focus/source/type/
# hub/timeline/order/hierarchy in src/lib/3d/KnowledgeGraph.svelte) all lay out by
# relationship; this one lays out by coordinates, and shows physical DISTANCE.
# The starter graph already carries the input: p:coordinates "lat, lon" on the
# campgrounds (and lat/lon in the NWS forecast URLs).

kb:spatial-force-layout rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Spatial / map force layout" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F59" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:principle    "Some concepts are best seen by RELATION (the current force modes); others by LOCATION. A place with GPS coordinates has a true position — the graph should be able to honour it, and show real physical distance, without forcing every other node onto a map." ;
               kpred:description  "Add a 'map' / 'place' force mode alongside the existing ones. Nodes with location facts are positioned by their coordinates; nodes without stay related-but-loose (or hidden) so mixed graphs still read. The mode DISPLAYS physical distance (e.g. the 327 mi / 5h drives in the starter graph) rather than spring-relation distance. Scale-aware: GPS is assumed to be on Earth's surface, so render with Earth's curvature + scale; astronomical coordinates place nodes in space (solar-system scale). Also the umbrella for improving how the starter graph reads across ALL force modes (it exercises timeline via scheduled-at/ends-at, type via its custom types, hub via people<->options, and now map via coordinates)." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:entity-types ;
               kpred:open-question "Portable plain-text location format — UNDECIDED. Must be plain text and easily portable. Accept multiple input formats (decimal lat/lon, DMS, geo: URIs, maybe WKT/GeoJSON-as-text) and normalise; the graph assumes bare GPS = Earth surface. Which canonical predicate(s) — reuse p:coordinates, or a typed geo predicate?" ;
               kpred:open-question "Earth model: how much geodesy is worth it (great-circle distance + a globe mesh) vs. a simple projected plane for small extents? Solar-system / space scale is a stretch goal." .

kb:int-game-engine rdf:type  ktype:Tool ;
               rdfs:label    "Open-source game engine (spatial rendering)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F59.1" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:spatial-force-layout ;
               kpred:description  "Consider an open-source game engine as an integration for richer spatial/3D rendering (globe, terrain, scale, physics) beyond what the in-app three.js view does — e.g. Godot (web export), Bevy (wasm), or a three.js/globe.gl layer that stays in-process. NO server exists for this yet (unlike the n8n + Indico servers), so it is roadmap-first. Weigh an in-process wasm/three approach (keeps the offline-first, no-server thesis) against a heavier engine that would need hosting." ;
               kpred:open-question "In-process (globe.gl / three-globe / Bevy-wasm, no server) vs. a hosted engine — the no-server, offline-first constraint strongly favours in-process." .

# -- Arrange → Page Layout Builder (F60) ---------------------------------------
# The "arrange" force mode (internally layout='order' — a manual drag-grid with
# numbered nodes, src/lib/3d/KnowledgeGraph2D.svelte) grows into a linear layout
# surface. Raised 2026-07-10. The insight: arranging nodes in a linear order +
# vertical/horizontal grouping IS page structure — so this becomes the bridge
# from graph arrangement to web-page layout building (F27 / F55 publishing).

kb:arrange-layout-builder rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Arrange → page layout builder" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F60" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:principle    "Arranging nodes in a linear order, with vertical stacking and horizontal grouping, is exactly a page's block layout (sections, rows, columns). The graph-view arrange tools should translate DIRECTLY into web-page layout building — the same gesture that orders the graph orders the page." ;
               kpred:description  "Give the arrange mode a VERTICAL-SCROLL, FULL-SCREEN mode: instead of a fixed canvas grid, nodes flow top-to-bottom in a scrollable column, and can be grouped horizontally (side-by-side) to form rows. You accomplish both a vertical layout (stacked sections) and a horizontal layout (columns within a row) by arranging + ordering. That arrangement is captured on the nodes (order + row/column grouping, extending the existing nodeOrder / hnav ordering) and maps to the published page's block structure. Bridges F27 graph-publishing (WebPage nodes -> content/*.md) and F55.4 custom pages: the arrange canvas becomes a lightweight page-layout builder where blocks are graph nodes." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:publishing-v2 ;
               kpred:open-question "Where is the arrangement stored — extend nodeOrder + the hnav ordering predicates (urn:reckons:nav/order|layer) with a row/column grouping, or a dedicated layout predicate? It must round-trip to the page block model." ;
               kpred:open-question "Full-screen vertical scroll implies a DOM/scroll surface, not the fixed canvas the other force modes use — is arrange a special non-canvas mode, or a canvas with virtual scroll? DOM makes the page-layout mapping far more direct." .

# -- Integration Plugin SDK (F61) ----------------------------------------------
# With so many integrations planned (LLM providers, Google, Meshy, Indico, n8n,
# GitHub, GitLab, a game engine, image-gen, asset tooling …), formalise a
# plug-in architecture + a documented process for adding one. Raised 2026-07-10.

kb:integration-plugin-sdk rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Integration Plugin SDK" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F61" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:principle    "The integration count is the product surface — it must scale by CONVENTION, not bespoke wiring each time. Separate integrations behind one plug-in contract so a new one is 'implement the interface + register', and the app discovers capabilities generically." ;
               kpred:description  "Architecturally separate the integrations (today ad-hoc under src/lib/integrations/<company>/) behind a plug-in SDK: a typed contract each integration implements — id/label, declared CAPABILITIES (ingest / sync / storage / generation / auth), a config schema (keys, endpoints) that renders its own Settings UI, an auth lifecycle, and typed entry points. A registry discovers plug-ins and the app drives them by capability rather than by name. The LLM provider backends (claude/openai/gemini/ollama/wasm/…, already per-task-selectable) are the pattern to generalise across ALL integration kinds. Enables: swap GitHub<->GitLab (F55.3), plug-in asset-gen tools (F58.8 orchestration), a game-engine plug-in (F59.1), and cloud-storage providers (F55.2) without touching the core." ;
               kpred:description  "DEVELOPMENT PROCESS (to be documented as part of this): (1) scaffold from an integration template; (2) implement the capability interface(s); (3) declare config schema + auth; (4) register the plug-in; (5) capability-level tests against a fake backend (the drive-sync fake-Drive test is the model); (6) a Settings→Integrations entry renders automatically from the config schema. Documented in the Architecture KB, not a new docs/*.md (TTL-first policy)." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:llm-providers ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:gp-gitlab ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:gp-cloud-storage ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:gen-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:int-game-engine .

# -- Integration Orchestration & Scheduling (F64) ------------------------------
# Beyond one-shot integration calls: chain integrations with trigger events,
# dependencies, and schedules. Raised 2026-07-10.

kb:integration-orchestration rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Integration orchestration & scheduling" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F64" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:principle    "Integrations must be INTERCONNECTABLE, with clearly definable trigger events, dependencies, and schedules — not just fire-and-forget. Example: a blogger's web page publishes ONLY AFTER the Facebook post is drafted. Order and timing are first-class." ;
               kpred:description  "Let a user define trigger events, dependencies BETWEEN integration actions, and schedules — so cross-integration flows are explicit and ordered (publish-after-draft, post-then-notify, nightly-sync). Two layers: (a) the user's own n8n owns the heavy multi-step automation (its native strength); (b) the app models the intent — trigger/dependency/schedule as graph facts — and hands it to n8n or runs light in-app schedules. Scheduling exists in Claude Code routines (CronCreate/ScheduleWakeup) as a pattern; here it is user-facing, per-graph. Plugs into the Integration Plugin SDK (F61) so any plug-in exposes trigger/action hooks." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:integration-plugin-sdk ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:n8n-cloud-sync ;
               kpred:open-question "How much orchestration lives IN Reckons.AI vs. delegated to n8n? Lean: model intent + simple schedules in-app, delegate complex multi-service flows to the user's n8n (its job), per the n8n-is-not-a-backend principle (F20)." .

# -- Entity Sets & Multi-node Grouping (F65) -----------------------------------
# A user-defined GROUPING of entities (a "set"), alongside entity types, with
# premade relating triples — creatable up front or from a selection in the graph.
# Raised 2026-07-10. Builds on the existing multi-select (Ctrl+click -> merge /
# relate in src/routes/(app)/+page.svelte).

kb:entity-sets rdf:type      ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Entity sets (multi-entity groupings)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F65" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/entity-sets.test.ts" ;
               kpred:remaining    "FIRST CUT SHIPPED (2026-07-10): batch multi-select in the graph -> '⬡ group as set' creates a first-class ktype:EntitySet node linked to members via urn:kbase:predicate/has-member (src/lib/rdf/entity-sets.ts; rendered via the new EntitySet built-in type; deletion-protected as a group). Term 'set' used in the UI. SHIPPED select→act (2026-07-10): selecting a set node dims the rest and spotlights the set + members; the set panel offers '⬡ select N members' to act on the group. REMAINING: (1) instantiate a set as a TEMPLATE (drop the whole cluster + premade relating triples up front); (2) extra ANALYZE options on a grouped selection; (3) less-clunky multi-select (lasso; the entry gesture is still canvas Ctrl+click); (4) minor: a set isn't findable by name in search (the label surfaces as a literal node, not the set entity)." ;
               kpred:principle    "Entity TYPES describe ONE node's kind; entity SETS describe a reusable GROUP of nodes + the relationships among them. A set is a customizable grouping — optionally with premade triples relating its members — that a user can define once and instantiate, the way types are reused." ;
               kpred:description  "Two entry points to the same concept: (1) MULTI-ENTITY CREATION — define a 'set' up front (members + optional premade relating triples), a template you instantiate to drop a whole related cluster at once (e.g. a 'trip' set = 2 people + 2 options + routes, like the starter graph's shape). Lives alongside entity types. (2) MULTI-NODE GROUPING IN THE GRAPH — select several nodes (extends the existing Ctrl+click multi-select) and GROUP them; a grouped selection unlocks additional ANALYZE options (analyze the subgraph as a unit) and a 'save as entity set' action that captures the members + their inter-relationships as a reusable set. Grouping also feeds F58.5 asset-assembly (a set is a natural generation subgraph) and F60 arrange (a set is a natural page section)." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:entity-types ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:meta-visual-generation ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:arrange-layout-builder ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:sets-xr ;
               kpred:open-question "Storage: is a set a first-class node (ktype:EntitySet) whose members are linked by a 'has-member' predicate, or a saved selection/template? First-class node makes it queryable + shareable and round-trips in TTL." .

kb:sets-xr rdf:type          ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Sets in VR / AR / XR" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F65.1" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:entity-sets ;
               kpred:principle    "Grouping nodes into a set is inherently SPATIAL — the natural gesture is to physically gather things. XR is where that becomes fluid: reach out, grab nodes, pull them into a pile, and that pile IS a set. It directly answers the 'multi-select is clunky' problem for sets." ;
               kpred:description  "Consider VR/AR/XR as the premier UI/UX for sets: in an immersive 3D graph, batch-select by looking/pointing or a lasso volume, GRAB nodes and gather them with hand/controller gestures, and drop them into a set; manipulate, split, and re-arrange sets in space (ties to F59 spatial layout + F60 arrange). Builds on the existing VR/AR shells (F7, VRShell/ARShell + WebXR) and the game-engine option (F59.1) for richer spatial rendering. XR turns the clunky Ctrl+click multi-select into a direct, embodied action." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:vr-ar-shells ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:spatial-force-layout ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:int-game-engine .

# -- Coding-Agent Context Dogfooding (F68) -------------------------------------
# The app's own TTL graphs used as CONDENSED, pre-reviewed context for the coding
# agents building it — the dogfooding of "information-dense instruction for future
# sessions / local offline agents." Raised 2026-07-10.

kb:agent-context-dogfooding rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               kpred:test-coverage "none" ;
               kpred:honest-note  "No automated test covers this feature (audited 2026-07-12, scripts/offline/status-evidence.ts). The status is still accurate — it IS shipped and in use; test coverage and deployment maturity are orthogonal, and pretending otherwise would be its own dishonesty. This is a declared RISK, not a hidden one: kb:honest-status requires the gap be visible rather than silent." ;
               rdfs:label    "Coding-agent context dogfooding" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F68" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:description  "Uses compressed, pre-reviewed subgraphs to speed up coding-agent sessions. The saving comes overwhelmingly from SELECTING a relevant subgraph rather than from the compact encoding (the format itself is worth ~18% vs grouped Turtle — measured, see kb:context-compression). Rather than re-reading the code and re-deriving the plan each session, an agent loads a dense, cross-linked graph carrying status, dependencies, tests, and decisions per feature — 80-90% fewer context-establishment tokens, and 77% fewer output tokens when drafting is delegated locally. Compressed subgraphs ground equal-or-better than the raw graph while costing far less, for cloud and offline alike." ;
               kpred:principle    "The graph is condensed context tracking for coding agents: instead of re-reading the codebase and re-deriving the plan each session, an agent loads a dense, cross-linked, pre-reviewed subgraph. Every feature captured here (status, deps, tests, decisions) is reusable instruction for the next session — cloud OR local/offline." ;
               kpred:measured     "CORRECTED 2026-07-12 — the 60-70% figure conflated two different things and overstated the format. MEASURED (mcp-server/src/__tests__/compress.test.ts): the compression FORMAT saves ~18% vs grouped Turtle (what a real .ttl looks like) and ~29% vs flat one-triple-per-line Turtle — NOT 60-70%. The large saving comes from SUBGRAPH SELECTION, not the encoding: a compressed subgraph feeds ~6x fewer input tokens than the raw graph (~50x cheaper per query than the whole ~116k-token graph raw) at EQUAL-or-BETTER grounding (raw scored 60% fact-coverage vs 80% compressed — needle-in-haystack). Grounded generation: compressed-context 79% cheaper; local-draft + Opus-review 77% cheaper on long outputs, same quality." ;
               kpred:estimate     "For coding-agent assistance (this build session as the sample): establishing task context via a compressed feature-area subgraph (~5-8k tokens) vs re-exploring code + re-deriving the plan (~30-60k tokens/feature) is a ~80-90% cut in context-establishment INPUT tokens per feature; output tokens drop ~77% when drafts are delegated to local models (Opus orchestrates + reviews). Compounding: this session added ~20 cross-linked feature entities — dense instruction a future/offline agent loads instead of re-deriving. CAVEAT: directional estimate; the reckons MCP was not connected this session, so the realized win was plan-grounding via the TTL graphs directly (no feature re-derivation, consistent status/deps), not the full kb_compress pipeline." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:local-offload ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:context-compression .

kb:settings-polish rdf:type  ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Settings polish + Publishing tab" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F69" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:description  "Refine ALL settings pages and add a PUBLISHING tab. Findings (2026-07-10): (1) the settings nav is COPY-PASTED across all 4 pages (backends / integrations / turtle / entity-types) with duplicated markup AND styles — extract a shared src/routes/(app)/settings/+layout.svelte so the nav/chrome live once; (2) the 'turtle' tab is MISLABELED — it's actually Shelly identity/personality/voice settings, not Turtle/RDF; rename it (e.g. 'shelly' or 'assistant'); (3) NEW 'publishing' tab to house the currently-scattered/absent publish settings — githubToken (used by publishSiteToGitHub, no UI today), site identity (kbTitle/kbDescription), and a link to Sveltia /admin; move 'semantic web' / publishing settings here; (4) audit for stale/older components + surfaced errors (user reports seeing some) — needs the specific errors/components identified. Do the shared-layout extraction FIRST so adding the tab doesn't multiply the duplication." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:has-part     kb:settings-unified-integrations ;
               kpred:done         "2026-07-11: the 'publishing' tab shipped (semantic web / LLM search export moved off backends; JSON-LD + llms.txt), with a nav link across the settings pages and a visual test. REMAINING: shared-layout dedup, rename the mislabeled 'turtle'(=Shelly) tab, and the unified-integrations rework (F69.1)." ;
               kpred:open-question "Which specific errors / older components are visible? Targeted fixes need them pointed out." .

kb:settings-unified-integrations rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Unified, categorized integrations settings" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F69.1" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:settings-polish ;
               kpred:principle    "The biggest settings mess is BACKENDS vs INTEGRATIONS — an artificial split. Everything is an integration. Present them as one surface, tagged by CATEGORY (what kind of thing) and by CAPABILITY (what workflow verb it serves), filterable either way." ;
               kpred:description  "Merge the 'backends' + 'integrations' tabs into ONE integrations surface. Tag each integration two ways: (a) CATEGORY — AI (LLM / VLM / code-agent / embedding / OCR / TTS-STT), Calendars (Google / Indico / iCal), Storage/Sync (local folder / Google Drive / GitHub / n8n / Nextcloud), etc.; (b) CAPABILITY — the app verbs it powers: Add (ingest/extract/OCR), Review, Analyze, Reckon. The verb view overlaps with category (an integration's category implies which verbs it serves), so offer FILTERS for either view — browse by category or by 'what powers Reckon'. Provider-status metadata already exists (provider-status.svelte.ts); this is the taxonomy + a filterable UI on top. Pairs naturally with the Integration Plugin SDK (F61): each plug-in DECLARES its category + capabilities, and the settings surface renders from that declaration." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:integration-plugin-sdk ;
               kpred:open-question "Store the taxonomy where — a static map now, or derived from each plug-in's declared category/capabilities once F61 lands (preferred, so it stays in sync)?" .

kb:local-ocr rdf:type        ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Local OCR (Ollama / WASM)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F70" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/visual/user-stories/ocr-ingest.test.ts" ;
               kpred:description  "Offline text-from-image, complementing the existing CLOUD OCR (Mistral, src/lib/integrations/parsers/mistral-ocr.ts — PDFs/images → markdown in ingest). Two local paths, both viable: (a) OLLAMA VLMs — PROVEN 2026-07-10: qwen2.5vl:7b (already installed for the VLM visual gate) OCR'd a full UI screenshot verbatim, every line correct, in ~78s at temp 0; qwen2.5vl:3b / granite3.2-vision are faster options. Reuses the VLM-gate plumbing (tests/visual/vision-local.ts). Slow for big images. (b) WASM — Tesseract.js (classic in-browser OCR, small ~2-4MB lang data, fast, fully offline) OR transformers.js OCR models (TrOCR / Florence-2 / GOT-OCR2 via @huggingface/transformers, already a dep). Use cases: an OFFLINE ingest OCR option (no Mistral key), and text extraction for the visual tests. SHIPPED 2026-07-11 with Tesseract.js (WASM): src/lib/integrations/parsers/local-ocr.ts (ocrImageLocal, lang data from cdn.jsdelivr — CSP-allowed); ingest images now try Mistral then FALL BACK to local OCR (so images always read offline) — also fixed a latent bug where api.mistral.ai was missing from the CSP connect-src (Mistral OCR was blocked for everyone). Visual harness: ocrScreenshot / normalizeOcr in tests/visual/vision-local.ts (invert+2x-upscale preprocessing recovers dark-UI text; assert substrings, not exact, on stylized fonts). qwen2.5vl VLM path remains for layout/semantic reads." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:visual-testing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:local-offload .

kb:ocr-visual-testing rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "OCR in visual testing" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F70.1" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:tested-by    "tests/visual/user-stories/ocr-visual.test.ts" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:local-ocr ;
               kpred:description  "Add OCR to the visual test harness so screenshots can be asserted on EXACT rendered text, not just the VLM 'does X appear' gate (F34). Recommended: Tesseract.js (WASM) for speed + determinism + offline; keep the qwen2.5vl VLM path (proven verbatim, but ~78s/image) for cases needing layout/semantic reading. E.g. assert the Publishing tab's nav reads 'backends publishing integrations turtle entity types' exactly — the qwen2.5vl OCR already did this correctly in the feasibility test. Complements analyzeText/analyzePixels in tests/visual/vision-local.ts." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:visual-testing .

# -- Content Orchestrator (F71) ------------------------------------------------
# Reframe: Reckons.AI is a CONTENT ORCHESTRATOR, not just a context manager. It
# doesn't only manage input context — it COMPOSES digital-asset OUTPUTS from the
# graph. Raised 2026-07-11.

kb:content-orchestrator rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Content Orchestrator" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F71" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:priority     "high" ;
               kpred:principle    "Content Orchestrator, not just Context manager: the graph is a SOURCE for composed outputs (a combined PDF, a doc, a set of images/3D), not only a store of reviewed context. Orchestration = clean, clear composition of digital assets FROM the graph." ;
               kpred:principle    "Scope by SELECTION, not the whole graph. Generate/compose from a chosen SET (F65 entity sets) or a set-selection menu — or the whole graph — the user picks the scope. 'Maybe both': a scope switch (this set / these sets / everything)." ;
               kpred:description  "Compose digital-asset outputs cleanly: COMBINE PDFs (merge several PDFs, or compose one PDF from selected graph content/WebPages), and other outputs (image collage, doc, 3D scene). Driven by set-selection menus that bound the output to a subgraph, so you're not forced to render the entire graph. Sits atop F58 meta-visual generation (output types PNG/PDF/GLB, F58.4), F58.5 asset+fact assembly (now scoped by a set), F58.7 file conversion (PDF composition), and F58.8 orchestration; F65 entity sets provide the selection scope. PDF composition is one of the most FEASIBLE near-term outputs (deterministic, OSS libs) — a good first Content-Orchestrator deliverable." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:entity-sets ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:meta-visual-generation ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:mvg-asset-assembly ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:gen-orchestration ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:review-anchored-generation .

